{"title_page": "Double-lumen endobronchial tube", "text_new": "[[File:Carlens.jpg|300px|thumb|right|A Carlens double-lumen endotracheal tube, commonly used for [[thoracic surgery|thoracic surgical]] operations such as [[VATS lobectomy]].]]\n\nA '''double-lumen endotracheal tube''' (also called '''double-lumen endobronchial tube''' or '''DLT''') is a type of [[endotracheal tube]] which is used in [[tracheal intubation]] during [[thoracic surgery]] and other medical conditions to achieve selective, one-sided [[Pulmonary ventilation|ventilation]] of either the right or the left lung.\n\n== Indications ==\nThere are several conditions that may make one-sided lung ventilation necessary. Absolute indications include separation of the right from the left lung to avoid spillage of blood or pus from an infected or bleeding side to the unaffected side. Relative indications include the collapse of one lung and the selective ventilation of the remaining lung in order to facilitate exposure of the anatomical structures to be operated on in thoracic surgeries, such as the repair of a thoracic [[aortic aneurysm]], [[pneumonectomy]] or [[lobectomy]].<ref name=\"web\">Miller, Ronald.D, Anesthesia, Fifth edition , [http://web.squ.edu.om/med-Lib/MED_CD/E_CDs/anesthesia/site/content/v04/040009r00.htm Section 4: Subspecialty Management, Chapter 48:Anesthesia for Thoracic Surgery] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531231149/http://web.squ.edu.om/med-Lib/MED_CD/E_CDs/anesthesia/site/content/v04/040009r00.htm |date=May 31, 2013 }}, published by Churchill Livingstone (2000)</ref>\n\n== Development and description ==\nA DLT is made up of two small-lumen endotracheal tubes of unequal length fixed side by side. The shorter tube ends in the [[Vertebrate trachea|trachea]] while the longer one is placed in either the left or right [[bronchus]] in order to selectively ventilate the left or right lung respectively. The first double-lumen tube used for bronchospirometry and later for one-lung [[anaesthesia]] in humans was introduced by Carlens in 1949.<ref>{{cite journal\n|author=Carlens E\n|title=A new flexible double-lumen catheter for bronchospirometry\n|journal=J Thorac Surg\n|volume=18\n|issue=5\n|pages=742\u2013746\n|date=October 1949\n|pmid=18149050}}</ref><ref>Brodsky J.B,  Lemmens H.J.M,  \"[http://lnx.mednemo.it/wp-content/uploads/2008/11/the-history-of-anesthesia-for-thoracic-surgery.pdf The history of anesthesia for thoracic surgery]\" Minerva anestesiologica, October 2007 p.519</ref> Modifications to the original Carlens tube have been introduced by White,<ref>White G.M.J, \"[http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/32/5/232.extract A New Double lumen tube]\", Oxford JournalsMedicine BJA Volume 32, Issue 5Pp. 232-234 (1960)</ref>  Robertshaw<ref>Robertshaw F.L, \"[http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/34/8/576.short LOW RESISTANCE DOUBLE-LUMEN ENDOBRONCHIAL TUBES]\" Oxford JournalsMedicine BJA Volume 34, Issue 8Pp. 576-579 (1962)</ref> and others. The most commonly used DLTs today are the Carlens and the Robertshaw tubes.<ref name=\"web\" /> These allow [[single-lung ventilation]] while the other lung is collapsed to make [[Thoracic surgery]] easier or possible. This may be necessary so as to facilitate the surgeon's view and access to relevant structures within the [[thoracic cavity]]. The deflated lung is re-inflated as surgery finishes to check for leakages or other injuries .\n\nThese tubes are typically [[coaxial]], with two separate channels and two separate openings. They incorporate an endotracheal lumen which terminates in the trachea and an endobronchial lumen, the distal tip of which is positioned 1\u20132&nbsp;cm into the right or left mainstem bronchus.\n\nProper placement of DLTs requires considerable clinical experience, various techniques for their insertion having been developed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Seo|first=JH|author2=Kwon, TK |author3=Jeon, Y |author4=Hong, DM |author5=Kim, HJ |author6= Bahk, JH |title=Comparison of techniques for double-lumen endobronchial intubation: 90{degrees} or 180{degrees} rotation during advancement through the glottis.|journal=British Journal of Anaesthesia|date=20 June 2013|pmid=23794671 |doi=10.1093/bja/aet203 |volume=111 |issue=5 |pages=812\u20137}}</ref><ref>El-Etr AA. Improved technic for insertion of the Carlens catheter. Anesth Analg. 1969 Sep-Oct;48(5):738-40. http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/content/48/5/738.full.pdf</ref> And there is a small simulator to help in the training of Carlens tube rotation maneuvers.<ref>de Menezes Lyra R. Glottis simulator. Anesth Analg. 1999 Jun;88(6):1422-3.[http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/cgi/reprint/88/6/1424.pdf]</ref>\n\nPlacement has been found to be easier with the aid of fiber optical equipment such as a [[bronchoscope]].<ref name=\"web\" /><ref>{{cite journal | author = Purugganan RV, Jackson TA, Heir JS, Wang H, Cata JP | year = 2012 | title = Video laryngoscopy versus direct laryngoscopy for double-lumen endotracheal tube intubation: a retrospective analysis | url = | journal = J Cardiothorac Vasc Anesth | volume = 26| issue = 5| pages = 845\u20138| pmid = 22361488 | doi = 10.1053/j.jvca.2012.01.014 }}</ref> Currently, flexible fiberoptic bronchoscopy examination is recommended before, during placement, and at the conclusion of the use of DLTs.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Campos|first=JH|title=Lung isolation techniques for patients with difficult airway.|journal=Current Opinion in Anesthesiology|date=February 2010|volume=23|issue=1|pages=12\u20137|pmid=19752725|doi=10.1097/ACO.0b013e328331e8a7|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/27fddf09351736e0e69750fa79c93812969a0ef9}}</ref>\n\n== Alternatives ==\nOther methods of achieving a one sided lung ventilation are the [[Univent tube]],<ref>J H Campos, D K Reasoner and J R Moyers, \"[http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/content/83/6/1268.short Comparison of a modified double-lumen endotracheal tube with a single-lumen tube with enclosed bronchial blocker]\" A & A December 1996 vol. 83 no. 6 1268-1272</ref> which has a single tracheal lumen and blocker, and other [[endobronchial blocker]]s.<ref>Campos, Javier H, \"[http://journals.lww.com/co-anesthesiology/Abstract/2007/02000/Which_device_should_be_considered_the_best_for.7.aspx Which device should be considered the best for lung isolation: double-lumen endotracheal tube versus bronchial blockers]\"  Current Opinion in Anesthesiology: February 2007 - Volume 20 - Issue 1 - p 27-31</ref>\n\nThe approach to ventilating each lung via a separate ventilator is called the DuoVent approach. This system operates by connecting both ventilators to a master control unit, allowing for synchrony between the two ventilators.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Combitube]]\n*[[Endotracheal tube]]\n*[[Airtraq]]\n*[[Laryngeal tube]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|last=Brodsky|first=JB|last2=Lemmens|first2=JM|title=Left Double-Lumen Tubes: Clinical Experience With 1,170 Patients|journal=Journal of Cardiothoracic and Vascular Anesthesia|volume=17|issue=3|pages=289\u201398|year=2003|pmid=12827573|pmc=|doi=10.1016/S1053-0770(03)00046-6|url=http://ether.stanford.edu/library/thoracic_anesthesia/One-Lung%20Ventilation/DLT%20Placement.pdf|archiveurl=https://zenodo.org/record/896726|archive-date=2017-09-23}}\n\n[[Category:Medical equipment]]\n[[Category:Anesthetic equipment]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Carlens.jpg|300px|thumb|right|A Carlens double-lumen endotracheal tube, commonly used for [[thoracic surgery|thoracic surgical]] operations such as [[VATS lobectomy]].]]\n\nA '''double-lumen endotracheal tube''' (also called '''double-lumen endobronchial tube''' or '''DLT''') is a type of [[endotracheal tube]] which is used in [[tracheal intubation]] during [[thoracic surgery]] and other medical conditions to achieve selective, one-sided [[Pulmonary ventilation|ventilation]] of either the right or the left lung.\n\n== Indications ==\nThere are several conditions that may make one-sided lung ventilation necessary. Absolute indications include separation of the right from the left lung to avoid spillage of blood or pus from an infected or bleeding side to the unaffected side. Relative indications include the collapse of one lung and the selective ventilation of the remaining lung in order to facilitate exposure of the anatomical structures to be operated on in thoracic surgeries, such as the repair of a thoracic [[aortic aneurysm]], [[pneumonectomy]] or [[lobectomy]].<ref name=\"web\">Miller, Ronald.D, Anesthesia, Fifth edition , [http://web.squ.edu.om/med-Lib/MED_CD/E_CDs/anesthesia/site/content/v04/040009r00.htm Section 4: Subspecialty Management, Chapter 48:Anesthesia for Thoracic Surgery] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531231149/http://web.squ.edu.om/med-Lib/MED_CD/E_CDs/anesthesia/site/content/v04/040009r00.htm |date=May 31, 2013 }}, published by Churchill Livingstone (2000)</ref>\n\n== Development and description ==\nA DLT is made up of two small-lumen endotracheal tubes of unequal length fixed side by side. The shorter tube ends in the [[Vertebrate trachea|trachea]] while the longer one is placed in either the left or right [[bronchus]] in order to selectively ventilate the left or right lung respectively. The first double-lumen tube used for bronchospirometry and later for one-lung [[anaesthesia]] in humans was introduced by Carlens in 1949.<ref>{{cite journal\n|author=Carlens E\n|title=A new flexible double-lumen catheter for bronchospirometry\n|journal=J Thorac Surg\n|volume=18\n|issue=5\n|pages=742\u2013746\n|date=October 1949\n|pmid=18149050}}</ref><ref>Brodsky J.B,  Lemmens H.J.M,  \"[http://lnx.mednemo.it/wp-content/uploads/2008/11/the-history-of-anesthesia-for-thoracic-surgery.pdf The history of anesthesia for thoracic surgery]\" Minerva anestesiologica, October 2007 p.519</ref> Modifications to the original Carlens tube have been introduced by White,<ref>White G.M.J, \"[http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/32/5/232.extract A New Double lumen tube]\", Oxford JournalsMedicine BJA Volume 32, Issue 5Pp. 232-234 (1960)</ref>  Robertshaw<ref>Robertshaw F.L, \"[http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/34/8/576.short LOW RESISTANCE DOUBLE-LUMEN ENDOBRONCHIAL TUBES]\" Oxford JournalsMedicine BJA Volume 34, Issue 8Pp. 576-579 (1962)</ref> and others. The most commonly used DLTs today are the Carlens and the Robertshaw tubes.<ref name=\"web\" /> These allow [[single-lung ventilation]] while the other lung is collapsed to make [[Thoracic surgery]] easier or possible. This may be necessary so as to facilitate the surgeon's view and access to relevant structures within the [[thoracic cavity]]. The deflated lung is re-inflated as surgery finishes to check for leakages or other injuries .\n\nThese tubes are typically [[coaxial]], with two separate channels and two separate openings. They incorporate an endotracheal lumen which terminates in the trachea and an endobronchial lumen, the distal tip of which is positioned 1\u20132&nbsp;cm into the right or left mainstem bronchus.\n\nProper placement of DLTs requires considerable clinical experience, various techniques for their insertion having been developed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Seo|first=JH|author2=Kwon, TK |author3=Jeon, Y |author4=Hong, DM |author5=Kim, HJ |author6= Bahk, JH |title=Comparison of techniques for double-lumen endobronchial intubation: 90{degrees} or 180{degrees} rotation during advancement through the glottis.|journal=British Journal of Anaesthesia|date=20 June 2013|pmid=23794671 |doi=10.1093/bja/aet203 |volume=111 |issue=5 |pages=812\u20137}}</ref><ref>El-Etr AA. Improved technic for insertion of the Carlens catheter. Anesth Analg. 1969 Sep-Oct;48(5):738-40. http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/content/48/5/738.full.pdf</ref> And there is a small simulator to help in the training of Carlens tube rotation maneuvers.<ref>de Menezes Lyra R. Glottis simulator. Anesth Analg. 1999 Jun;88(6):1422-3.[http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/cgi/reprint/88/6/1424.pdf]</ref>\n\nPlacement has been found to be easier with the aid of fiber optical equipment such as a [[bronchoscope]].<ref name=\"web\" /><ref>Purugganan RV, Jackson TA, Heir JS, Wang H, Cata JP. Video laryngoscopy versus direct laryngoscopy for double-lumen endotracheal tube intubation: a retrospective analysis  J Cardiothorac Vasc Anesth. 2012 Oct  {{PMID|22361488}}</ref> Currently, flexible fiberoptic bronchoscopy examination is recommended before, during placement, and at the conclusion of the use of DLTs.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Campos|first=JH|title=Lung isolation techniques for patients with difficult airway.|journal=Current Opinion in Anesthesiology|date=February 2010|volume=23|issue=1|pages=12\u20137|pmid=19752725|doi=10.1097/ACO.0b013e328331e8a7|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/27fddf09351736e0e69750fa79c93812969a0ef9}}</ref>\n\n== Alternatives ==\nOther methods of achieving a one sided lung ventilation are the [[Univent tube]],<ref>J H Campos, D K Reasoner and J R Moyers, \"[http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/content/83/6/1268.short Comparison of a modified double-lumen endotracheal tube with a single-lumen tube with enclosed bronchial blocker]\" A & A December 1996 vol. 83 no. 6 1268-1272</ref> which has a single tracheal lumen and blocker, and other [[endobronchial blocker]]s.<ref>Campos, Javier H, \"[http://journals.lww.com/co-anesthesiology/Abstract/2007/02000/Which_device_should_be_considered_the_best_for.7.aspx Which device should be considered the best for lung isolation: double-lumen endotracheal tube versus bronchial blockers]\"  Current Opinion in Anesthesiology: February 2007 - Volume 20 - Issue 1 - p 27-31</ref>\n\nThe approach to ventilating each lung via a separate ventilator is called the DuoVent approach. This system operates by connecting both ventilators to a master control unit, allowing for synchrony between the two ventilators.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Combitube]]\n*[[Endotracheal tube]]\n*[[Airtraq]]\n*[[Laryngeal tube]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal|last=Brodsky|first=JB|last2=Lemmens|first2=JM|title=Left Double-Lumen Tubes: Clinical Experience With 1,170 Patients|journal=Journal of Cardiothoracic and Vascular Anesthesia|volume=17|issue=3|pages=289\u201398|year=2003|pmid=12827573|pmc=|doi=10.1016/S1053-0770(03)00046-6|url=http://ether.stanford.edu/library/thoracic_anesthesia/One-Lung%20Ventilation/DLT%20Placement.pdf|archiveurl=https://zenodo.org/record/896726|archive-date=2017-09-23}}\n\n[[Category:Medical equipment]]\n[[Category:Anesthetic equipment]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-lumen_endobronchial_tube"}
{"title_page": "Tazz", "text_new": "{{short description|America professional wrestler, color commentator and radio personality}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Taz<!-- MATCH ARTICLE TITLE -->\n|image       = Tazz 2.jpg\n|caption     = Tazz in 2008\n|birthname   = Peter Senercia<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|names       = Kid Krush<ref name=\"OwW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/t/tazz.html|title=Taz profile|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br />The Tasmanian Devil<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />The Tazmaniac<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />'''Taz'''<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />Tazz<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|weight      = {{convert|248|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|10|11}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]],<br>[[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n|family      = [[Chris Chetti]] (cousin)\n|resides     = [[Long Island, New York]],<br>[[United States]]\n|billed      = [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|The Red Hook Section of Brooklyn, New York]]<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Johnny Rodz]]<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|debut       = {{start date|1987|6|3}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|retired     = {{end date|2002|4|1}}<ref name=Tazzvision/>\n}}\n'''Peter Senercia''' (born October 11, 1967),<ref name=\"slambio\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/tazz.html|title=Taz bio|accessdate=July 20, 2007|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> better known by the [[ring name]] '''Taz''' (spelled '''Tazz''' in WWE) is an American [[radio host|radio personality]], [[color commentator]] and retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] currently signed to [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW).\n\nHe is known for his work in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW), where he was a [[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|World Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwchampionship|title=ECW Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Television Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Television Championship|World Television Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtvtitlehistory|title=ECW TV Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|three time]] [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|World Tag Team Champion]],<ref name=\"ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ecw/ecw-t.html|title=ECW World Tag Team Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtaghistory|title=ECW Tag Team Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|two time (and the inaugural)]] [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"SolieFTW\" /> and the third (and final) ECW [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)|Triple Crown Champion]].\n\nHis [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment]] (WWF/E) career as an in-ring performer came to an early end in 2002 and subsequently saw him transition into a color-commentary role, which he continued to do until his contract with WWE expired in April 2009.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|title=Tazz's WWE Alumni Bio|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408030616/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|archivedate=April 8, 2009}}</ref> Two months later, Senerchia debuted in [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] at their [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]] pay-per-view under his previous '''Taz''' ring name and eventually reprised his role as a color commentator for TNA's broadcasts, replacing [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]].\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Training, World Wrestling Council and independent circuit (1987\u20131993) ===\nSenerchia began wrestling in [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) and made his professional wrestling debut on June 3, 1987<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twnpnews.com/information/misc/debut.shtml|title=::Wrestler Debut Dates:: TWNP-Wrestling News and Information|first=Kevin|last=Romano|website=www.twnpnews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwbts.com/features/debut.html|title=PWBTS 2000 - Your #1 News Source - \"As I See It\" - Bob Magee|first=Fritz|last=Capp|website=www.pwbts.com}}</ref> in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], after being trained by [[Johnny Rodz]]. He wrestled as Kid Krush before moving on to the [[Ring name|name]] The Tazmaniac, which he would use variations of for the rest of his career.<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In the early 1990s, as The Tazmaniac, he wrestled for [[International World Class Championship Wrestling]] (IWCCW) and held its [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship|Light Heavyweight Championship]] for six months in 1991.<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/icw/icw-lh.html|title=ICW/IWCCW Light Heavyweight Title|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref> He would follow [[Tony Rumble]] in leaving IWCCW to join the newly established [[Century Wrestling Alliance]] (CWA). He would also tour in [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW).\n\nWrestling as The Tasmaniac, Senerchia had his first [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) match on August 19, 1991, when he was defeated by [[Ray Odyssey]]. Appearing as The Tazmaniac, he then made his only appearance ever in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) when he defeated [[Joey Maggs]] in a dark match at a ''[[WCW Saturday Night|Saturday Night]]'' taping in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] on February 8, 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw93.htm |title=WCW 1993 |publisher=Thehistoryofwwe.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-22}}</ref> He would then make his second appearance in the WWF on May 5, 1993. Wrestling in a dark match at a Wrestling Challenge taping in Portland, ME, Tazmaniac would beat [[Scotty 2 Hotty|Scott Taylor]]. He would go on to make two additional appearances on [[house show]]s in [[New Jersey]] on June 29 and June 30, losing to [[Jim Powers]] on each occasion.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm</ref>\n\n=== NWA Eastern / Extreme Championship Wrestling ===\n==== Early years and injury (1993\u20131995) ====\nIn October 1993, he and Joe Chetti (brother of [[Chris Chetti]]) debuted in the [[Philadelphia]]-based Eastern Championship Wrestling (ECW), prior to its name change to [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]], as the [[tag team]] The Tazmaniacs.<ref name=\"OwW\"/> When that team broke up, he was put into another team with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]], with whom he won the [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|Tag Team Championship]] twice.<ref name=\"ECWTT\"/><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/> During his second reign as Tag Team Champion with Sullivan, The Tazmaniac became a double champion when he also won the [[ECW World Television Championship|Television Championship]] for one night in March 1994.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> For most of the rest of the year he floated around the tag ranks, teaming with different partners. He held the title once more, this time with [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]], until Sabu was [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimately]] fired by ECW owner [[Paul Heyman]] for [[No-show (professional wrestling)|no-showing]] an event in favor of touring Japan for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]].<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\">{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW|Rise and Fall of ECW, The]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref> In August 1994, The Tazmaniac competed in a [[NWA World Title Tournament|one-night eight-man tournament]] for the vacant [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]], losing to [[Shane Douglas]] in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"Williams2013\">{{cite book|author=Scott E. Williams|title=Hardcore History: The Extremely Unauthorized Story of ECW|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4EQtAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT56|date=13 December 2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Company, Incorporated|isbn=978-1-61321-582-1|pages=56\u201357}}</ref><ref name=\"Loverro2007\">{{cite book|author=Thom Loverro|title=The Rise & Fall of ECW: Extreme Championship Wrestling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0dlOLyCj6YC|date=22 May 2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-6156-9|pages=67\u201378}}</ref>\n\nThe Tazmaniac was put out of action by a legit injury for much of 1995. On July 15, during a tag team match [[2 Cold Scorpio]] and [[Dean Malenko]] delivered a [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Aided piledriver|spike piledriver]] to him, and though he knew it was about to be performed, he did not have time to properly protect himself. As he explained on the DVD documentary ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]'', \"I landed right on my forehead and just jacked my whole neck back and that was it.\" The neck injury was so bad that, according to [[Tommy Dreamer]], hospital staff couldn't believe he'd walked into the hospital where he sought help after the match. Though he was unable to wrestle, Paul Heyman continued to pay him per their oral agreement, forging a loyalty between the men.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n==== Rise to superstardom (1995\u20131996) ====\nFollowing his neck injury, Taz made appearances with [[The Steiner Brothers]], even standing in their corner during matches with [[The Eliminators]] and getting physical with [[Jason Knight|Jason]]. It was at the [[November to Remember (1995)|November to Remember]] event, when Taz turned heel and joined up with referee [[Bill Alfonso]]. Working as the special referee for Alfonso's match with ECW commissioner [[Tod Gordon]], Taz refused to count to three and assaulted Gordon, then making the count for Alfonso. In his post-match promo, he claimed that no one was looking after him while he was injured and that no one cared (though Heyman was still paying him, the [[kayfabe]] story was that he had been forgotten and that Alfonso was the one helping him keep food on his family's table). He was also angry that Sabu was brought back in that very night.\n\nTaz returned to the ring on December 19, 1995 at Holiday Hell with a new look and wrestling style. The new character had him clad in a black/orange [[wiktionary:singlet|singlet]] and exhibiting a more physically intense in-ring style, focusing his offense on mat wrestling and [[suplex]]es (inspired by working with The Steiner Brothers), which announcer [[Joey Styles]] dubbed ''[[#In wrestling|Taz-Plexes]]'', earning him the nickname \"The Human Suplex Machine\". He also debuted his ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Half nelson choke|Tazmission]]''/Katahajime finishing maneuver, causing opponents to [[Submission (combat sport)|tap out]] to signal their submission as in [[mixed martial arts]] instead of nodding their head or vocally saying \"yes\". This quirk was soon picked up by other companies throughout the country.<ref>{{cite episode|title=12/17/95|series=History of ECW|network=[[WWE Classics On Demand]]| airdate=2007-08-14}}</ref> Heading into the summer, Taz began feuding with Tommy Dreamer, joining up with [[Brian Lee (wrestler)|Brian Lee]] to face Dreamer and [[Terry Gordy]] and later Dreamer and [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams]]. Taz also developed a friendship with The Eliminators, based on mutual respect, and they occasionally involved themselves in his matches. [[Perry Saturn]] and Taz were both trainers at ECW's [[House of Hardcore]] wrestling school. For a while, some of the students, including Mako and [[Chris Chetti]], would accompany Taz and Alfonso to the ring as a faction known as Team Taz.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\nAt [[November to Remember (1996)|November to Remember]], things seemed to come full circle, as Taz stormed to the ring and interrupted Styles and \"stole Paul E.'s thunder\" by announcing that there would be a \"big show in the first quarter of the new year\", basically telling the fans in attendance that ECW's first [[pay-per-view]] was on the horizon. At that \"big show\", he guaranteed that Sabu would finally face him. Later that night, he came out to force Scorpio to leave the ring and went on an angry tirade, abusing Bob Artese and holding him hostage in the ring. Taz demanded Sabu come out and face him, and twice even led the crowd in a \"Sabu, Sabu\" chant to get him to enter the ring.  Several officials and wrestlers came out and Taz eventually got his hands on Paul E. The lights went out and when they came back on, Sabu was in the ring, across from Taz. This was the first time they had been in the ring together since early 1995. Before they could lock up, the lights went out again.\n\nDuring Sabu's match, where he teamed with [[Rob Van Dam]] to face The Eliminators and [[The Gangstas]] in a three-way dance, Taz attempted to attack his former partner, but Van Dam saved Sabu and was choked out in the aisle. This distraction caused Sabu to get hit with ''Total Elimination'' and his team lost. Taz also began a mini-feud with Rob Van Dam, dominating him in every match and was also out for a short time to get surgery on his injured shoulder. As 1996 ended and 1997 began, Taz and Sabu continued to try getting at one another, with no actual contact.\n\n==== World Television Champion (1997\u20131998) ====\nEarly in 1997, the antagonism between Sabu and Taz was growing, as Taz attacked Sabu's partner, Rob Van Dam, costing the team matches with The Eliminators and other teams. In the months leading to ECW's [[ECW Barely Legal|first pay-per-view]], Taz would choke out low-level wrestlers with the ''Tazmission'' due to viewing his matches as secondary to his rivalry with Sabu. He then dominated another series of matches with Van Dam before meeting Sabu at [[ECW Barely Legal|Barely Legal]], where Taz defeated him with the ''Tazmission'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1997b.html#041397|title=Barely Legal 1997 results| accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> only to have his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]] [[Bill Alfonso]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Turn|turn]] on him and join Sabu and his partner [[Rob Van Dam]].<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In response, Taz began teaming with [[Chris Candido]] to face Sabu and Van Dam.\n\nTwo months later at [[Wrestlepalooza (1997)|Wrestlepalooza]], Taz lost to Sabu in the rematch, marking his first loss since 1995. However, later in the night, he won the World Television Championship from [[Shane Douglas]] to begin his second reign.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> He defended the title against all comers, including Douglas, [[Lance Storm]], [[John Kronus]], [[Al Snow]], [[Jerry Lynn]] and [[Chris Candido]]. Throughout late 1997, Taz began feuding with The Triple Threat in addition to Sabu and Van Dam, where he sometimes teamed up with [[Tommy Dreamer]] during the feud. At [[November to Remember (1997)|November to Remember]], he issued a challenge to World Heavyweight Champion Bam Bam Bigelow. The two would eventually meet, after Bigelow turned on Taz in a match against Shane Douglas and Chris Candido. Taz would ultimately lose the title to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]] at [[Living Dangerously (1998)|Living Dangerously]] on March 1, 1998.\n\nAfter losing the World Television Championship, Taz was elevated into the World Heavyweight Championship picture. In May 1998, with Shane Douglas injured and unable to wrestle, Taz was given an old World Television Championship belt painted orange\u2014his trademark color\u2014and began [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|cutting promos]], declaring himself the [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]] at [[It Ain't Seinfeld]]. Though the championship was unsanctioned [[Kayfabe|in storyline]], it was defended at ECW shows until Douglas was healthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1998c.html#080298|title=Heat Wave 1998 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just before winning the World Heavyweight Championship, Taz \"gave\" the FTW Heavyweight Title to long-time foe Sabu in a match where he physically pulled Sabu on top of him to allow him to get the pin.<ref name=\"SolieFTW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/ftwecw.html|title=Fuck The World title history|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n\n==== World Heavyweight Champion and departure (1999) ====\nTaz finally defeated Shane Douglas for the World Heavyweight Championship at [[Guilty as Charged (1999)|Guilty as Charged]], thus ending Douglas' year-long reign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999a.html#011099|title=Guilty as Charged 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz was supposed to defend the title against [[Chris Candido]] in his first televised title defense at [[House Party (1999)|House Party]] but Douglas attacked Candido before the match and took his place, whom Taz defeated to retain the title in his first successful title defense. He would then begin a feud with Sabu over Taz's World Heavyweight Championship and Sabu's FTW Heavyweight Championship. The rivalry culminated in a title unification match at the [[Living Dangerously (1999)|Living Dangerously]] pay-per-view, where Taz defeated Sabu to unify the FTW Heavyweight Championship into the World Heavyweight Championship. He would begin his next rivalry with Chris Candido, whom he defeated to retain the title at [[CyberSlam (1999)|CyberSlam]]. The two were scheduled to a rematch at [[Hardcore Heaven (1999)|Hardcore Heaven]], which Taz quickly won. However, he was attacked by [[Dudley Boyz]] after the match, leading to a title defense against [[Bubba Ray Dudley|Buh Buh Ray Dudley]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] in the main event later that night, which Taz won to retain the title. Taz then successfully defended the title against Candido on the June 4 episode of ''Hardcore TV'' to end the rivalry.\n\nTaz made his next successful title defense against [[Spike Dudley]] in a Falls Count Anywhere match on the June 25 episode of ''Hardcore TV''. He would begin feuding with the members of [[Steve Corino]]'s [[The Network (professional wrestling)|new rising stable]], primarily [[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]. Taz successfully defended the World Heavyweight Championship against Tajiri at [[Hostile City Showdown (1999)|Hostile City Showdown]], the [[Heat Wave (1999)|Heat Wave]] pay-per-view and the September 3 episode of ''[[ECW on TNN]]''. During that time, Taz signed with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]], losing the title as the first man eliminated in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|three-way dance]] at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999c.html#091999|title=Anarchy Rulz 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher= Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> This ended his eight-month reign at 252 days. As he walked out of the ring, a large portion of the ECW locker room joined him on the entrance ramp to give him an emotional sendoff. After being off of ECW television for most of the fall, he wrestled one final match as an ECW performer at [[November to Remember (1999)|November to Remember]], losing to [[Rob Van Dam]] via [[Pin (wrestling)|pinfall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999d.html#110799|title=November to Remember 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz's final televised match in ECW aired on the November 13 episode of ''Hardcore TV'', in which he received a rematch against Mike Awesome for the World Heavyweight Championship, which he lost. In the DVD ''The Rise and Fall of ECW'', Taz said that he signed with the WWE because he was in the top of the company and he lost his passion.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (2000-2009)===\n==== Hardcore Champion, feud with Jerry Lawler and The Alliance (2000\u20132002) ====\n{{Main|The Invasion (professional wrestling)|l1=The Invasion|The Alliance (professional wrestling)|l2=The Alliance}}\nAfter being contacted by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) and [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) in 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021065026/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-10-21|title=Defection Inspection|last=Anderson|first=Steve|accessdate=July 17, 2008|date=October 2000|publisher=Wrestling Digest}}</ref> Taz debuted for the WWF, with the slightly modified ring name Tazz, at the [[Royal Rumble (2000)|2000 Royal Rumble]] with a win over the previously undefeated [[Kurt Angle]] at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/rumble.html#00|title=Royal Rumble 2000 results|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just a few months after Tazz arrived in the WWF, [[Mike Awesome]], the man he had lost the ECW World Heavyweight Championship to at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]], secretly signed with WCW. Legal wrangling by Paul Heyman prevented Awesome from taking the championship belt with him, and in a bizarre piece of professional wrestling history, ECW and WWF officials agreed to have Tazz, a WWF wrestler, make a surprise appearance at an ECW show to defeat Awesome, a WCW wrestler, for the ECW World Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/02/19/3645984.html|title=Mike Awesome found dead|last= Oliver|first=Greg|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Sports]]}}</ref> Tazz held the title for ten days before losing it to [[Tommy Dreamer]], during which time he wore it on various WWF shows, including an episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' where he lost to the [[WWE Championship|WWF Champion]] [[Triple H]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |title=SmackDown! results \u2013 2000 |accessdate=July 23, 2007 |publisher=Online World of Wrestling |quote=April 20, 2000[...]WWF World Champion, Triple H, b ECW World Champion, Tazz |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012210938/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref> However, [[Vince McMahon]] later expressed some regret over [[Professional wrestling booker|booking]] Tazz to lose to Triple H.<ref>{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing the ECW World Heavyweight Championship, Tazz was placed into contention for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]], but never won the title. In the summer, after taking time off for an arm injury, he was turned into a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous character]] and placed into a feud with [[color commentator]] [[Jerry Lawler]].<ref name=\"slamint\"/> The feud included matches at [[SummerSlam (2000)|SummerSlam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#2000|title=SummerSlam 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> and [[Unforgiven 2000|Unforgiven]], which they split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/unforgiven.html#2000|title=Unforgiven 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Tazz was only able to pick up the Unforgiven win when he received help from [[Raven (wrestler)|Raven]], who had returned to the company. Afterwards, the duo formed a [[tag team]] that lasted until November.\n\nWhen the [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|Invasion]] angle began, Tazz acted as \"the voice of the [[The Alliance (professional wrestling)|WCW/ECW Alliance]]\", sticking up for them and speaking on their behalf whenever possible. He eventually left the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|stable]] after the leader [[Steve Austin|Stone Cold Steve Austin]] criticized his decision to stay on commentary rather than help ECW owner [[Stephanie McMahon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011108.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 8, 2001|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\n==== Commentator (2002\u20132009) ====\nWith injuries mounting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/01082008/articles/tazzshoots|title=Tazz shoots again|accessdate=January 11, 2008|author=Tazz|publisher=WWE|date=January 10, 2008}}</ref> Tazz began performing part-time commentary on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' in October 2000. He joined the ''SmackDown!'' team in February 2001 after Jerry Lawler quit the company, after calling his first [[pay-per-view]] on [[No Way Out (2001)|No Way Out]] with [[Jim Ross]], as well as becoming one of the trainers for the joint WWF/[[MTV]] produced reality series ''[[WWE Tough Enough|Tough Enough]]''.<ref name=\"slamint\">{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingBiosT/tazz_01aug-can.html|title=Tazz talks: ECW, Tough Enough, WWF|last=Kapur|first=Bob |accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Wrestling]]}}</ref> Lawler returned to the company on November 19, 2001 and resumed his place as commentator, with Tazz becoming both a wrestler and a commentator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011122.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 22, 2001|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> In January 2002, he and [[Spike Dudley]] won the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael McAvennie|title=WWE The Yearbook: 2003 Edition|publisher=Pocket Books|year=2003|pages=13\u201316}}</ref> holding it for over a month before losing it to [[Billy and Chuck]].<ref name=\"WT-WWFTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwf/wwf-t.html|title=WWWF / WWF / WWE World Tag Team Title|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tazz.jpg|left|thumb|250x250px|Tazz signing autographs in 2006]]\nWhen World Wrestling Entertainment [[WWE Brand Extension|split into two brands]], Tazz was put on the [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]] brand, where he resumed his color commentator duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 April 4, 2002|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917154817/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|archivedate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> Not long after he retired from the ring, he became a full-time broadcaster.<ref name=Tazzvision>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2005/05/30/1063493.html|title=Tuning into Tazzvision|last=Zerr|first=Scott|accessdate =July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Wrestling]]}}</ref> He co-hosted ''SmackDown!'' for World Wrestling Entertainment until a third brand, [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]], was introduced in 2006, at which point he became the color commentator for that show.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/> He was also the co-host, with Joey Styles, of ''History of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'' on [[WWE 24/7 Classics]], a show that re-airs archived episodes of the original ECW's weekly television programs. Before and during episodes he and Styles provide insight into the storylines, inner workings, and general ambiance of ECW at the time\u2014as they remember it.\n\nIn February 2006, Tazz and his ''SmackDown!'' broadcasting partner, [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]], hosted a week-long trial run of a show on [[Howard 100 and Howard 101|Howard 101]] on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], but the show was not picked up. He also hosted a talk show on [[WNYL (FM)|92.3 Free FM]] at sporadic intervals between late summer 2006 and early 2007, but it was not picked up and the station changed formats, replacing all post morning programming with music. On June 11, 2006, Tazz wrestled his final match to date, defeating Jerry Lawler at [[ECW One Night Stand (2006)|ECW One Night Stand]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ECW One Night Stand PPV Results 6/11/06 New York City, New York|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1150081251.shtml| publisher=WrestleView|first=Adam|last=Martin|date=June 11, 2006|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the recording of the April 29, 2008 episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'', Tazz's broadcast partner [[Mike Adamle]] abruptly walked off set prior to the main event. Moments later, after reading the promo for the upcoming pay-per-view, Tazz walked out as well, leaving the main event with no commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2008/04/30/5428941.html|title=ECW: Announcing follies overshadow decent show|first=Matt|last=Bishop|accessdate=April 30, 2008|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Sports]]}}</ref> On December 13, 2010, Tazz joined Right After Wrestling and said that it \"pisses him off\" when companies try to re-create the original ECW. He stated that the original ECW worked because \"It was that era, that group of people, that leader in Paul Heyman. We were that little engine that could.\"<ref>[http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 Podcasts | The Score] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120715182953/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 |date=2012-07-15 }}. Radio.thescore.com (December 13, 2010). Retrieved on 2011-11-29.</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, Tazz filled in for [[Mick Foley]] as a color commentator on the SmackDown brand, while Raw wrestler [[Matt Striker]] filled in for Tazz on the ECW brand. When Foley left the company, Tazz became the permanent color commentator for the SmackDown brand once again. On April 3, 2009, Tazz left WWE when his contract expired. His WWE.com profile was moved from the active SmackDown roster list to the alumni list for a short time before being completely removed, confirming his departure from the company.\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2009\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Tazz and Mike Tenay.jpg|thumb|Taz (left) with his commentary partner, [[Mike Tenay]] in July 2010]]\nAt [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]], Senercia, under his Taz ring name, made his official [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) debut during [[Samoa Joe]]'s match against [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]], revealing himself to be Joe's [[Kayfabe|on-screen]] adviser and consequently a [[heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] as well as an ally of the [[The Main Event Mafia|Main Event Mafia]]. The match ending was booked as Taz's presence enabling Joe to recover from Sting's ''[[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Scorpion Deathlock]]'' and win the match via submission after applying the ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Rear naked choke|Coquina Clutch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victory Road PPV Results \u2013 7/19/09|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2009/1248058721.php|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=July 19, 2009|work=WrestleView|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the August 20, 2009 episode of ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', Taz replaced [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]] as the promotion's color commentator and also became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] upon stating that he was only loosely associated with the Mafia and that he had taught Joe everything he knew and that it was now up to Joe to use his newfound skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/font_color_770000_KELLER_S_TAKE_font_11/article_34814.shtml|title=Keller's TNA Impact report 8/20: Results, star ratings, thoughts, observations, quotebook|authorlink=Wade Keller|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=August 27, 2009|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Impact: Blueprint gets the tables|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/08/21/10541866.html?cid=rsssportswrestling|last=Sokol|first=Bryan|author2=Sokol, Chris |date=August 21, 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> In May 2012, Taz began appearing as a judge in the monthly [[TNA Gut Check|Gut Check]] segment on ''Impact Wrestling''.<ref name=\"TNA3May\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_61084.shtml|title=Turner's TNA Impact Wrestling Results 5/3: Roode and RVD pick opponents for each other, Gut Check fall-out, Flair calls out Hogan|author=Turner, Scott|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch Newsletter|PWTorch.com]]|date=May 4, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref><!-- DO NOT ADD WEEK BY WEEK EVENTS, RUMORS OR SPECULATION. THIS INCLUDES ANNOUNCED MATCHES THAT HAVE NOT YET OCCURRED. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A NEWS SITE BUT AN ONLINE ENCYCLOPEDIA. Please see the articles \"Wikipedia:What Wikipedia is not\" and \"Wikipedia:Guide to writing better articles\" for more information. -->\n\nOn the January 17, 2013 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz was a [[groomsman]] at the wedding between [[Mark LoMonaco|Bully Ray]] and [[Brooke Hogan]]. As Ray and Brooke exchanged their vows, Taz interrupted the ceremony and proclaimed himself to be a member of [[Aces & Eights]] after revealing a [[kutte]] underneath his coat, turning heel again in the process. Following his revelation, Aces & Eights ambushed the ceremony and attacked Ray, his groomsmen [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Spike Dudley|Brother Runt]] and Brooke's father [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67961.shtml|title= KELLER'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/17: The Bully Ray-Brooke Hogan Wedding Episode \u2013 What happened? Did Hulk accompany Brooke? Did the wedding end without a hitch?|date=January 17, 2013|last=Keller|first=Wade|accessdate=January 17, 2013|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following week on ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz revealed that he joined Aces & Eights because of his desire to be a member of a group that adheres to a higher power.<ref name=TazReason>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_68117.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 1/24: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Hardy vs. Daniels TNA Title match, Teflon Taz, wedding fall-out (updated w/Box Score)|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref> On the November 21 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Aces & Eights was forced to disband after Bully Ray lost to [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Anderson]], which also saw Anderson retain his career in TNA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_74692.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 11/21: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Turning Point\" Impact - TNA Title tournament continues, Bully vs. Anderson, more|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2015, it was  officially announced that Taz had departed TNA.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=JohnGaburick|author=John Gaburick|number=588450682002255873|date=15 April 2015|title=After 5+ years TNA &amp; Taz have mutually decided to part ways. A champ in the ring &amp; on the mic, we wish him nothing but success! @OfficialTAZ}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=OfficialTAZ|author=TAZ|number=588450023613988864|date=15 April 2015|title=Like to thank TNA Wrestling for the opportunity to apply my craft for past several years. Best wishes to them in the future.}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE (2016) ===\nIn November 2016, Tazz made an appearance on the [[WWE Network]] special, ''The Authentic Untold Story of ECW'', alongside former ECW management Paul Hayman and wrestlers Bubba Ray Dudley, D-Von Dudley, and Tommy Dreamer. In the one-hour special hosted by [[Corey Graves]], the guests talked about their experiences in ECW and the promotion's legacy on professional wrestling.\n\n=== All Elite Wrestling (2019\u2013present) ===\nOn October 12, 2019, Taz made a guest appearance for [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), where he appeared on the October 22nd edition of ''[[AEW Dark]]'' as a guest commentator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/10/taz-to-guest-commentate-on-this-week-aew-dark-660674/|title=Taz To Guest Commentate On This Week's AEW Dark|publisher=Wrestling Inc.}}</ref> On November 9, 2019, Taz made his guest appearance during [[AEW Full Gear|Full Gear]] as the pre-show commentator. On the January 1, 2020 episode of ''[[AEW Dynamite]]'', Taz made his ''Dynamite'' debut on commentary filling in for [[Tony Schiavone]]. On January 16, 2020, it was announced that Taz had officially signed a multi-year deal with AEW, and he is set to be a member of the AEW broadcast team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sescoops.com/taz-signs-multi-year-deal-with-aew/amp/|title=Taz Signs Multi-Year Deal With AEW|work=SEScoops.com|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling style and persona ==\nTazz's character was influenced by [[The Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]], [[The Steiner Brothers]] and [[Wild Samoans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-talks-early-disagreement-vince-mcmahon/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Talks About An Early Disagreement With Vince McMahon}}</ref> Tazz is nicknamed the \"Human Suplex Machine\" due to his wide array of suplex variations he would utilise in matches. His finishing move, the ''Tazmission'', is a half nelson choke with bodyscissors. He also sometimes combined this submission with a suplex, creating a half nelson choke suplex, called the ''Tazmission-Plex''.<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/the-50-coolest-maneuvers-of-all-time/page-16 |title=the 50 coolest maneuvers of all time|date=February 21, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014|publisher=WWE}}</ref> He has also claimed to have named the T-Bone Suplex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-says-named-t-bone-suplex/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Says He Named The T-Bone Suplex}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe has a [[tattoo]] of the [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Looney Tunes Tasmanian Devil]] on his upper right bicep accompanied by the legend Taz. His action figures produced by [[Jakks Pacific]] does not include the character, but does include the name. He has a self designed tattoo on his left lower bicep. Senerchia played [[Secondary school|high school]] [[high school football|football]]. Senerchia also studied [[judo]] prior to entering the professional wrestling circuit, reaching a second-degree black belt.<ref name=tazz73>Loverro, Thom (2006). ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]''. Pocket Books. {{ISBN|978-1-41-651312-4}}. p. 73</ref>  He is a fan of the [[New York Mets]], [[New York Knicks]], [[Philadelphia 76ers]], and the [[New York Jets]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==In other media==\nBeginning in 2018, Senercia was a nationally syndicated morning radio personality, co-hosting ''Taz and The Moose'' with Marc \"The Moose\" Malusis on [[CBS Sports Radio]] weekdays from 6-9 a.m. Eastern.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbssports.radio.com/shows/taz-and-moose|title=Taz & The Moose - CBS Sports Radio}}</ref> In December 2019, Senercia announced he was leaving the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://barrettsportsmedia.com/2019/12/17/taz-to-exit-cbs-sports-radio/|title=Taz To Exit CBS Sports Radio|date=2019-12-17|website=Barrett Sports Media|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>  \n\nSenercia also has his own podcast, called ''The Taz Show'', (formerly known as ''The Human Podcast Machine)'', where he discusses the latest in the professional wrestling world. The show has since discontinued. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.com/taz-show|title=The Taz Show|date=2018-04-30|website=RADIO.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nSenercia (as Tazz) appears as a playable character in ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007|SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]'' and ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009|SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n\n=== Amateur wrestling ===\n* Empire States Heavyweight Championship<ref>Noted by [[Joey Styles]] during the [[November to Remember 1997|1997 November to Remember]] broadcast</ref>\n\n=== Professional wrestling ===\n* '''[[Century Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n** [[CWA Cruiserweight Championship|CWA Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWA Cruiserweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"slambio\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/lhtcwa2.html|title=Solie's Title Histories: CWA - CENTURY WRESTLING ALLIANCE|website=www.solie.org}}</ref>\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern/Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=\"SolieFTW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Television Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Television Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/>\n** [[ECW World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|3 times]]) \u2013 with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]] (2)<sup>1</sup> and [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]] (1)<ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/>\n** Third [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of ECW Triple Crown Champions|ECW Triple Crown Champion]]\n* '''[[International World Class Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\"/>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 10 of the 500 best singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/1999.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 1999|accessdate=November 24, 2015|publisher=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him No. 147 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the \"[[PWI Years]]\" in 2003\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|3 times]])<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/hardcore-championship|title=Hardcore Championship|website=WWE}}</ref>\n** [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Spike Dudley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|title=World Tag Team Championship \u2013 Tazz & Spike Dudley|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024180601/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|archivedate=2012-10-24}}</ref>\n*'''''[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Gimmick|Worst Gimmick]] (2013) <small>[[Aces & Eights]]</small><ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=35}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (2013)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=26}}</ref>\n*'''Victory Championship Wrestling'''\n**VCW Hall of Fame (Class of 2018)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Peter Senerchia|Tazz}}\n* {{IMDb name|name = Peter Senerchia}}\n* {{WWE superstar|name = Tazz}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131103092937/http://www.impactwrestling.com/roster/Wrestler-Roster/item/1622-taz TNA profile]\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{Aces & Eights}}\n{{ECW Championship}}\n{{ECW World Television Championship}}\n{{ECW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n{{World Tag Team Championship (WWE)}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taz}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Aces and Eights members]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling personnel]]\n[[Category:American color commentators]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:ECW Heavyweight Champions/ECW World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Tag Team Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LIU Post alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:The Alliance (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:The Dangerous Alliance members]]\n[[Category:The ECW Originals members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American radio personality, color commentator and professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Taz<!-- MATCH ARTICLE TITLE -->\n|image       = Tazz 2.jpg\n|caption     = Tazz in 2008\n|birthname   = Peter Senercia<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|names       = Kid Krush<ref name=\"OwW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/t/tazz.html|title=Taz profile|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br />The Tasmanian Devil<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />The Tazmaniac<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />'''Taz'''<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />Tazz<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|weight      = {{convert|248|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|10|11}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]],<br>[[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n|family      = [[Chris Chetti]] (cousin)\n|resides     = [[Long Island, New York]],<br>[[United States]]\n|billed      = [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|The Red Hook Section of Brooklyn, New York]]<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Johnny Rodz]]<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|debut       = {{start date|1987|6|3}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|retired     = {{end date|2002|4|1}}<ref name=Tazzvision/>\n}}\n'''Peter Senercia''' (born October 11, 1967),<ref name=\"slambio\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/tazz.html|title=Taz bio|accessdate=July 20, 2007|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> better known by the [[ring name]] '''Taz''' (spelled '''Tazz''' in WWE) is an American [[radio host|radio personality]], [[color commentator]] and retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] currently signed to [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW).\n\nHe is known for his work in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW), where he was a [[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|World Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwchampionship|title=ECW Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Television Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Television Championship|World Television Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtvtitlehistory|title=ECW TV Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|three time]] [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|World Tag Team Champion]],<ref name=\"ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ecw/ecw-t.html|title=ECW World Tag Team Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtaghistory|title=ECW Tag Team Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|two time (and the inaugural)]] [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"SolieFTW\" /> and the third (and final) ECW [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)|Triple Crown Champion]].\n\nHis [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment]] (WWF/E) career as an in-ring performer came to an early end in 2002 and subsequently saw him transition into a color-commentary role, which he continued to do until his contract with WWE expired in April 2009.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|title=Tazz's WWE Alumni Bio|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408030616/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|archivedate=April 8, 2009}}</ref> Two months later, Senerchia debuted in [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] at their [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]] pay-per-view under his previous '''Taz''' ring name and eventually reprised his role as a color commentator for TNA's broadcasts, replacing [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]].\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Training, World Wrestling Council and independent circuit (1987\u20131993) ===\nSenerchia began wrestling in [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) and made his professional wrestling debut on June 3, 1987<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twnpnews.com/information/misc/debut.shtml|title=::Wrestler Debut Dates:: TWNP-Wrestling News and Information|first=Kevin|last=Romano|website=www.twnpnews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwbts.com/features/debut.html|title=PWBTS 2000 - Your #1 News Source - \"As I See It\" - Bob Magee|first=Fritz|last=Capp|website=www.pwbts.com}}</ref> in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], after being trained by [[Johnny Rodz]]. He wrestled as Kid Krush before moving on to the [[Ring name|name]] The Tazmaniac, which he would use variations of for the rest of his career.<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In the early 1990s, as The Tazmaniac, he wrestled for [[International World Class Championship Wrestling]] (IWCCW) and held its [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship|Light Heavyweight Championship]] for six months in 1991.<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/icw/icw-lh.html|title=ICW/IWCCW Light Heavyweight Title|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref> He would follow [[Tony Rumble]] in leaving IWCCW to join the newly established [[Century Wrestling Alliance]] (CWA). He would also tour in [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW).\n\nWrestling as The Tasmaniac, Senerchia had his first [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) match on August 19, 1991, when he was defeated by [[Ray Odyssey]]. Appearing as The Tazmaniac, he then made his only appearance ever in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) when he defeated [[Joey Maggs]] in a dark match at a ''[[WCW Saturday Night|Saturday Night]]'' taping in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] on February 8, 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw93.htm |title=WCW 1993 |publisher=Thehistoryofwwe.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-22}}</ref> He would then make his second appearance in the WWF on May 5, 1993. Wrestling in a dark match at a Wrestling Challenge taping in Portland, ME, Tazmaniac would beat [[Scotty 2 Hotty|Scott Taylor]]. He would go on to make two additional appearances on [[house show]]s in [[New Jersey]] on June 29 and June 30, losing to [[Jim Powers]] on each occasion.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm</ref>\n\n=== NWA Eastern / Extreme Championship Wrestling ===\n==== Early years and injury (1993\u20131995) ====\nIn October 1993, he and Joe Chetti (brother of [[Chris Chetti]]) debuted in the [[Philadelphia]]-based Eastern Championship Wrestling (ECW), prior to its name change to [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]], as the [[tag team]] The Tazmaniacs.<ref name=\"OwW\"/> When that team broke up, he was put into another team with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]], with whom he won the [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|Tag Team Championship]] twice.<ref name=\"ECWTT\"/><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/> During his second reign as Tag Team Champion with Sullivan, The Tazmaniac became a double champion when he also won the [[ECW World Television Championship|Television Championship]] for one night in March 1994.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> For most of the rest of the year he floated around the tag ranks, teaming with different partners. He held the title once more, this time with [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]], until Sabu was [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimately]] fired by ECW owner [[Paul Heyman]] for [[No-show (professional wrestling)|no-showing]] an event in favor of touring Japan for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]].<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\">{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW|Rise and Fall of ECW, The]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref> In August 1994, The Tazmaniac competed in a [[NWA World Title Tournament|one-night eight-man tournament]] for the vacant [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]], losing to [[Shane Douglas]] in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"Williams2013\">{{cite book|author=Scott E. Williams|title=Hardcore History: The Extremely Unauthorized Story of ECW|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4EQtAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT56|date=13 December 2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Company, Incorporated|isbn=978-1-61321-582-1|pages=56\u201357}}</ref><ref name=\"Loverro2007\">{{cite book|author=Thom Loverro|title=The Rise & Fall of ECW: Extreme Championship Wrestling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0dlOLyCj6YC|date=22 May 2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-6156-9|pages=67\u201378}}</ref>\n\nThe Tazmaniac was put out of action by a legit injury for much of 1995. On July 15, during a tag team match [[2 Cold Scorpio]] and [[Dean Malenko]] delivered a [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Aided piledriver|spike piledriver]] to him, and though he knew it was about to be performed, he did not have time to properly protect himself. As he explained on the DVD documentary ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]'', \"I landed right on my forehead and just jacked my whole neck back and that was it.\" The neck injury was so bad that, according to [[Tommy Dreamer]], hospital staff couldn't believe he'd walked into the hospital where he sought help after the match. Though he was unable to wrestle, Paul Heyman continued to pay him per their oral agreement, forging a loyalty between the men.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n==== Rise to superstardom (1995\u20131996) ====\nFollowing his neck injury, Taz made appearances with [[The Steiner Brothers]], even standing in their corner during matches with [[The Eliminators]] and getting physical with [[Jason Knight|Jason]]. It was at the [[November to Remember (1995)|November to Remember]] event, when Taz turned heel and joined up with referee [[Bill Alfonso]]. Working as the special referee for Alfonso's match with ECW commissioner [[Tod Gordon]], Taz refused to count to three and assaulted Gordon, then making the count for Alfonso. In his post-match promo, he claimed that no one was looking after him while he was injured and that no one cared (though Heyman was still paying him, the [[kayfabe]] story was that he had been forgotten and that Alfonso was the one helping him keep food on his family's table). He was also angry that Sabu was brought back in that very night.\n\nTaz returned to the ring on December 19, 1995 at Holiday Hell with a new look and wrestling style. The new character had him clad in a black/orange [[wiktionary:singlet|singlet]] and exhibiting a more physically intense in-ring style, focusing his offense on mat wrestling and [[suplex]]es (inspired by working with The Steiner Brothers), which announcer [[Joey Styles]] dubbed ''[[#In wrestling|Taz-Plexes]]'', earning him the nickname \"The Human Suplex Machine\". He also debuted his ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Half nelson choke|Tazmission]]''/Katahajime finishing maneuver, causing opponents to [[Submission (combat sport)|tap out]] to signal their submission as in [[mixed martial arts]] instead of nodding their head or vocally saying \"yes\". This quirk was soon picked up by other companies throughout the country.<ref>{{cite episode|title=12/17/95|series=History of ECW|network=[[WWE Classics On Demand]]| airdate=2007-08-14}}</ref> Heading into the summer, Taz began feuding with Tommy Dreamer, joining up with [[Brian Lee (wrestler)|Brian Lee]] to face Dreamer and [[Terry Gordy]] and later Dreamer and [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams]]. Taz also developed a friendship with The Eliminators, based on mutual respect, and they occasionally involved themselves in his matches. [[Perry Saturn]] and Taz were both trainers at ECW's [[House of Hardcore]] wrestling school. For a while, some of the students, including Mako and [[Chris Chetti]], would accompany Taz and Alfonso to the ring as a faction known as Team Taz.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\nAt [[November to Remember (1996)|November to Remember]], things seemed to come full circle, as Taz stormed to the ring and interrupted Styles and \"stole Paul E.'s thunder\" by announcing that there would be a \"big show in the first quarter of the new year\", basically telling the fans in attendance that ECW's first [[pay-per-view]] was on the horizon. At that \"big show\", he guaranteed that Sabu would finally face him. Later that night, he came out to force Scorpio to leave the ring and went on an angry tirade, abusing Bob Artese and holding him hostage in the ring. Taz demanded Sabu come out and face him, and twice even led the crowd in a \"Sabu, Sabu\" chant to get him to enter the ring.  Several officials and wrestlers came out and Taz eventually got his hands on Paul E. The lights went out and when they came back on, Sabu was in the ring, across from Taz. This was the first time they had been in the ring together since early 1995. Before they could lock up, the lights went out again.\n\nDuring Sabu's match, where he teamed with [[Rob Van Dam]] to face The Eliminators and [[The Gangstas]] in a three-way dance, Taz attempted to attack his former partner, but Van Dam saved Sabu and was choked out in the aisle. This distraction caused Sabu to get hit with ''Total Elimination'' and his team lost. Taz also began a mini-feud with Rob Van Dam, dominating him in every match and was also out for a short time to get surgery on his injured shoulder. As 1996 ended and 1997 began, Taz and Sabu continued to try getting at one another, with no actual contact.\n\n==== World Television Champion (1997\u20131998) ====\nEarly in 1997, the antagonism between Sabu and Taz was growing, as Taz attacked Sabu's partner, Rob Van Dam, costing the team matches with The Eliminators and other teams. In the months leading to ECW's [[ECW Barely Legal|first pay-per-view]], Taz would choke out low-level wrestlers with the ''Tazmission'' due to viewing his matches as secondary to his rivalry with Sabu. He then dominated another series of matches with Van Dam before meeting Sabu at [[ECW Barely Legal|Barely Legal]], where Taz defeated him with the ''Tazmission'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1997b.html#041397|title=Barely Legal 1997 results| accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> only to have his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]] [[Bill Alfonso]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Turn|turn]] on him and join Sabu and his partner [[Rob Van Dam]].<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In response, Taz began teaming with [[Chris Candido]] to face Sabu and Van Dam.\n\nTwo months later at [[Wrestlepalooza (1997)|Wrestlepalooza]], Taz lost to Sabu in the rematch, marking his first loss since 1995. However, later in the night, he won the World Television Championship from [[Shane Douglas]] to begin his second reign.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> He defended the title against all comers, including Douglas, [[Lance Storm]], [[John Kronus]], [[Al Snow]], [[Jerry Lynn]] and [[Chris Candido]]. Throughout late 1997, Taz began feuding with The Triple Threat in addition to Sabu and Van Dam, where he sometimes teamed up with [[Tommy Dreamer]] during the feud. At [[November to Remember (1997)|November to Remember]], he issued a challenge to World Heavyweight Champion Bam Bam Bigelow. The two would eventually meet, after Bigelow turned on Taz in a match against Shane Douglas and Chris Candido. Taz would ultimately lose the title to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]] at [[Living Dangerously (1998)|Living Dangerously]] on March 1, 1998.\n\nAfter losing the World Television Championship, Taz was elevated into the World Heavyweight Championship picture. In May 1998, with Shane Douglas injured and unable to wrestle, Taz was given an old World Television Championship belt painted orange\u2014his trademark color\u2014and began [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|cutting promos]], declaring himself the [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]] at [[It Ain't Seinfeld]]. Though the championship was unsanctioned [[Kayfabe|in storyline]], it was defended at ECW shows until Douglas was healthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1998c.html#080298|title=Heat Wave 1998 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just before winning the World Heavyweight Championship, Taz \"gave\" the FTW Heavyweight Title to long-time foe Sabu in a match where he physically pulled Sabu on top of him to allow him to get the pin.<ref name=\"SolieFTW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/ftwecw.html|title=Fuck The World title history|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n\n==== World Heavyweight Champion and departure (1999) ====\nTaz finally defeated Shane Douglas for the World Heavyweight Championship at [[Guilty as Charged (1999)|Guilty as Charged]], thus ending Douglas' year-long reign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999a.html#011099|title=Guilty as Charged 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz was supposed to defend the title against [[Chris Candido]] in his first televised title defense at [[House Party (1999)|House Party]] but Douglas attacked Candido before the match and took his place, whom Taz defeated to retain the title in his first successful title defense. He would then begin a feud with Sabu over Taz's World Heavyweight Championship and Sabu's FTW Heavyweight Championship. The rivalry culminated in a title unification match at the [[Living Dangerously (1999)|Living Dangerously]] pay-per-view, where Taz defeated Sabu to unify the FTW Heavyweight Championship into the World Heavyweight Championship. He would begin his next rivalry with Chris Candido, whom he defeated to retain the title at [[CyberSlam (1999)|CyberSlam]]. The two were scheduled to a rematch at [[Hardcore Heaven (1999)|Hardcore Heaven]], which Taz quickly won. However, he was attacked by [[Dudley Boyz]] after the match, leading to a title defense against [[Bubba Ray Dudley|Buh Buh Ray Dudley]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] in the main event later that night, which Taz won to retain the title. Taz then successfully defended the title against Candido on the June 4 episode of ''Hardcore TV'' to end the rivalry.\n\nTaz made his next successful title defense against [[Spike Dudley]] in a Falls Count Anywhere match on the June 25 episode of ''Hardcore TV''. He would begin feuding with the members of [[Steve Corino]]'s [[The Network (professional wrestling)|new rising stable]], primarily [[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]. Taz successfully defended the World Heavyweight Championship against Tajiri at [[Hostile City Showdown (1999)|Hostile City Showdown]], the [[Heat Wave (1999)|Heat Wave]] pay-per-view and the September 3 episode of ''[[ECW on TNN]]''. During that time, Taz signed with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]], losing the title as the first man eliminated in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|three-way dance]] at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999c.html#091999|title=Anarchy Rulz 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher= Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> This ended his eight-month reign at 252 days. As he walked out of the ring, a large portion of the ECW locker room joined him on the entrance ramp to give him an emotional sendoff. After being off of ECW television for most of the fall, he wrestled one final match as an ECW performer at [[November to Remember (1999)|November to Remember]], losing to [[Rob Van Dam]] via [[Pin (wrestling)|pinfall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999d.html#110799|title=November to Remember 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz's final televised match in ECW aired on the November 13 episode of ''Hardcore TV'', in which he received a rematch against Mike Awesome for the World Heavyweight Championship, which he lost. In the DVD ''The Rise and Fall of ECW'', Taz said that he signed with the WWE because he was in the top of the company and he lost his passion.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (2000-2009)===\n==== Hardcore Champion, feud with Jerry Lawler and The Alliance (2000\u20132002) ====\n{{Main|The Invasion (professional wrestling)|l1=The Invasion|The Alliance (professional wrestling)|l2=The Alliance}}\nAfter being contacted by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) and [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) in 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021065026/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-10-21|title=Defection Inspection|last=Anderson|first=Steve|accessdate=July 17, 2008|date=October 2000|publisher=Wrestling Digest}}</ref> Taz debuted for the WWF, with the slightly modified ring name Tazz, at the [[Royal Rumble (2000)|2000 Royal Rumble]] with a win over the previously undefeated [[Kurt Angle]] at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/rumble.html#00|title=Royal Rumble 2000 results|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just a few months after Tazz arrived in the WWF, [[Mike Awesome]], the man he had lost the ECW World Heavyweight Championship to at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]], secretly signed with WCW. Legal wrangling by Paul Heyman prevented Awesome from taking the championship belt with him, and in a bizarre piece of professional wrestling history, ECW and WWF officials agreed to have Tazz, a WWF wrestler, make a surprise appearance at an ECW show to defeat Awesome, a WCW wrestler, for the ECW World Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/02/19/3645984.html|title=Mike Awesome found dead|last= Oliver|first=Greg|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Sports]]}}</ref> Tazz held the title for ten days before losing it to [[Tommy Dreamer]], during which time he wore it on various WWF shows, including an episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' where he lost to the [[WWE Championship|WWF Champion]] [[Triple H]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |title=SmackDown! results \u2013 2000 |accessdate=July 23, 2007 |publisher=Online World of Wrestling |quote=April 20, 2000[...]WWF World Champion, Triple H, b ECW World Champion, Tazz |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012210938/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref> However, [[Vince McMahon]] later expressed some regret over [[Professional wrestling booker|booking]] Tazz to lose to Triple H.<ref>{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing the ECW World Heavyweight Championship, Tazz was placed into contention for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]], but never won the title. In the summer, after taking time off for an arm injury, he was turned into a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous character]] and placed into a feud with [[color commentator]] [[Jerry Lawler]].<ref name=\"slamint\"/> The feud included matches at [[SummerSlam (2000)|SummerSlam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#2000|title=SummerSlam 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> and [[Unforgiven 2000|Unforgiven]], which they split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/unforgiven.html#2000|title=Unforgiven 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Tazz was only able to pick up the Unforgiven win when he received help from [[Raven (wrestler)|Raven]], who had returned to the company. Afterwards, the duo formed a [[tag team]] that lasted until November.\n\nWhen the [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|Invasion]] angle began, Tazz acted as \"the voice of the [[The Alliance (professional wrestling)|WCW/ECW Alliance]]\", sticking up for them and speaking on their behalf whenever possible. He eventually left the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|stable]] after the leader [[Steve Austin|Stone Cold Steve Austin]] criticized his decision to stay on commentary rather than help ECW owner [[Stephanie McMahon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011108.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 8, 2001|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\n==== Commentator (2002\u20132009) ====\nWith injuries mounting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/01082008/articles/tazzshoots|title=Tazz shoots again|accessdate=January 11, 2008|author=Tazz|publisher=WWE|date=January 10, 2008}}</ref> Tazz began performing part-time commentary on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' in October 2000. He joined the ''SmackDown!'' team in February 2001 after Jerry Lawler quit the company, after calling his first [[pay-per-view]] on [[No Way Out (2001)|No Way Out]] with [[Jim Ross]], as well as becoming one of the trainers for the joint WWF/[[MTV]] produced reality series ''[[WWE Tough Enough|Tough Enough]]''.<ref name=\"slamint\">{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingBiosT/tazz_01aug-can.html|title=Tazz talks: ECW, Tough Enough, WWF|last=Kapur|first=Bob |accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Wrestling]]}}</ref> Lawler returned to the company on November 19, 2001 and resumed his place as commentator, with Tazz becoming both a wrestler and a commentator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011122.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 22, 2001|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> In January 2002, he and [[Spike Dudley]] won the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael McAvennie|title=WWE The Yearbook: 2003 Edition|publisher=Pocket Books|year=2003|pages=13\u201316}}</ref> holding it for over a month before losing it to [[Billy and Chuck]].<ref name=\"WT-WWFTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwf/wwf-t.html|title=WWWF / WWF / WWE World Tag Team Title|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tazz.jpg|left|thumb|250x250px|Tazz signing autographs in 2006]]\nWhen World Wrestling Entertainment [[WWE Brand Extension|split into two brands]], Tazz was put on the [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]] brand, where he resumed his color commentator duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 April 4, 2002|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917154817/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|archivedate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> Not long after he retired from the ring, he became a full-time broadcaster.<ref name=Tazzvision>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2005/05/30/1063493.html|title=Tuning into Tazzvision|last=Zerr|first=Scott|accessdate =July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Wrestling]]}}</ref> He co-hosted ''SmackDown!'' for World Wrestling Entertainment until a third brand, [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]], was introduced in 2006, at which point he became the color commentator for that show.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/> He was also the co-host, with Joey Styles, of ''History of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'' on [[WWE 24/7 Classics]], a show that re-airs archived episodes of the original ECW's weekly television programs. Before and during episodes he and Styles provide insight into the storylines, inner workings, and general ambiance of ECW at the time\u2014as they remember it.\n\nIn February 2006, Tazz and his ''SmackDown!'' broadcasting partner, [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]], hosted a week-long trial run of a show on [[Howard 100 and Howard 101|Howard 101]] on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], but the show was not picked up. He also hosted a talk show on [[WNYL (FM)|92.3 Free FM]] at sporadic intervals between late summer 2006 and early 2007, but it was not picked up and the station changed formats, replacing all post morning programming with music. On June 11, 2006, Tazz wrestled his final match to date, defeating Jerry Lawler at [[ECW One Night Stand (2006)|ECW One Night Stand]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ECW One Night Stand PPV Results 6/11/06 New York City, New York|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1150081251.shtml| publisher=WrestleView|first=Adam|last=Martin|date=June 11, 2006|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the recording of the April 29, 2008 episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'', Tazz's broadcast partner [[Mike Adamle]] abruptly walked off set prior to the main event. Moments later, after reading the promo for the upcoming pay-per-view, Tazz walked out as well, leaving the main event with no commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2008/04/30/5428941.html|title=ECW: Announcing follies overshadow decent show|first=Matt|last=Bishop|accessdate=April 30, 2008|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Sports]]}}</ref> On December 13, 2010, Tazz joined Right After Wrestling and said that it \"pisses him off\" when companies try to re-create the original ECW. He stated that the original ECW worked because \"It was that era, that group of people, that leader in Paul Heyman. We were that little engine that could.\"<ref>[http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 Podcasts | The Score] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120715182953/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 |date=2012-07-15 }}. Radio.thescore.com (December 13, 2010). Retrieved on 2011-11-29.</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, Tazz filled in for [[Mick Foley]] as a color commentator on the SmackDown brand, while Raw wrestler [[Matt Striker]] filled in for Tazz on the ECW brand. When Foley left the company, Tazz became the permanent color commentator for the SmackDown brand once again. On April 3, 2009, Tazz left WWE when his contract expired. His WWE.com profile was moved from the active SmackDown roster list to the alumni list for a short time before being completely removed, confirming his departure from the company.\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2009\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Tazz and Mike Tenay.jpg|thumb|Taz (left) with his commentary partner, [[Mike Tenay]] in July 2010]]\nAt [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]], Senercia, under his Taz ring name, made his official [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) debut during [[Samoa Joe]]'s match against [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]], revealing himself to be Joe's [[Kayfabe|on-screen]] adviser and consequently a [[heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] as well as an ally of the [[The Main Event Mafia|Main Event Mafia]]. The match ending was booked as Taz's presence enabling Joe to recover from Sting's ''[[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Scorpion Deathlock]]'' and win the match via submission after applying the ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Rear naked choke|Coquina Clutch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victory Road PPV Results \u2013 7/19/09|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2009/1248058721.php|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=July 19, 2009|work=WrestleView|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the August 20, 2009 episode of ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', Taz replaced [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]] as the promotion's color commentator and also became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] upon stating that he was only loosely associated with the Mafia and that he had taught Joe everything he knew and that it was now up to Joe to use his newfound skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/font_color_770000_KELLER_S_TAKE_font_11/article_34814.shtml|title=Keller's TNA Impact report 8/20: Results, star ratings, thoughts, observations, quotebook|authorlink=Wade Keller|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=August 27, 2009|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Impact: Blueprint gets the tables|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/08/21/10541866.html?cid=rsssportswrestling|last=Sokol|first=Bryan|author2=Sokol, Chris |date=August 21, 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> In May 2012, Taz began appearing as a judge in the monthly [[TNA Gut Check|Gut Check]] segment on ''Impact Wrestling''.<ref name=\"TNA3May\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_61084.shtml|title=Turner's TNA Impact Wrestling Results 5/3: Roode and RVD pick opponents for each other, Gut Check fall-out, Flair calls out Hogan|author=Turner, Scott|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch Newsletter|PWTorch.com]]|date=May 4, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref><!-- DO NOT ADD WEEK BY WEEK EVENTS, RUMORS OR SPECULATION. THIS INCLUDES ANNOUNCED MATCHES THAT HAVE NOT YET OCCURRED. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A NEWS SITE BUT AN ONLINE ENCYCLOPEDIA. Please see the articles \"Wikipedia:What Wikipedia is not\" and \"Wikipedia:Guide to writing better articles\" for more information. -->\n\nOn the January 17, 2013 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz was a [[groomsman]] at the wedding between [[Mark LoMonaco|Bully Ray]] and [[Brooke Hogan]]. As Ray and Brooke exchanged their vows, Taz interrupted the ceremony and proclaimed himself to be a member of [[Aces & Eights]] after revealing a [[kutte]] underneath his coat, turning heel again in the process. Following his revelation, Aces & Eights ambushed the ceremony and attacked Ray, his groomsmen [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Spike Dudley|Brother Runt]] and Brooke's father [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67961.shtml|title= KELLER'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/17: The Bully Ray-Brooke Hogan Wedding Episode \u2013 What happened? Did Hulk accompany Brooke? Did the wedding end without a hitch?|date=January 17, 2013|last=Keller|first=Wade|accessdate=January 17, 2013|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following week on ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz revealed that he joined Aces & Eights because of his desire to be a member of a group that adheres to a higher power.<ref name=TazReason>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_68117.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 1/24: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Hardy vs. Daniels TNA Title match, Teflon Taz, wedding fall-out (updated w/Box Score)|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref> On the November 21 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Aces & Eights was forced to disband after Bully Ray lost to [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Anderson]], which also saw Anderson retain his career in TNA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_74692.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 11/21: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Turning Point\" Impact - TNA Title tournament continues, Bully vs. Anderson, more|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2015, it was  officially announced that Taz had departed TNA.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=JohnGaburick|author=John Gaburick|number=588450682002255873|date=15 April 2015|title=After 5+ years TNA &amp; Taz have mutually decided to part ways. A champ in the ring &amp; on the mic, we wish him nothing but success! @OfficialTAZ}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=OfficialTAZ|author=TAZ|number=588450023613988864|date=15 April 2015|title=Like to thank TNA Wrestling for the opportunity to apply my craft for past several years. Best wishes to them in the future.}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE (2016) ===\nIn November 2016, Tazz made an appearance on the [[WWE Network]] special, ''The Authentic Untold Story of ECW'', alongside former ECW management Paul Hayman and wrestlers Bubba Ray Dudley, D-Von Dudley, and Tommy Dreamer. In the one-hour special hosted by [[Corey Graves]], the guests talked about their experiences in ECW and the promotion's legacy on professional wrestling.\n\n=== All Elite Wrestling (2019\u2013present) ===\nOn October 12, 2019, Taz made a guest appearance for [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), where he appeared on the October 22nd edition of ''[[AEW Dark]]'' as a guest commentator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/10/taz-to-guest-commentate-on-this-week-aew-dark-660674/|title=Taz To Guest Commentate On This Week's AEW Dark|publisher=Wrestling Inc.}}</ref> On November 9, 2019, Taz made his guest appearance during [[AEW Full Gear|Full Gear]] as the pre-show commentator. On the January 1, 2020 episode of ''[[AEW Dynamite]]'', Taz made his ''Dynamite'' debut on commentary filling in for [[Tony Schiavone]]. On January 16, 2020, it was announced that Taz had officially signed a multi-year deal with AEW, and he is set to be a member of the AEW broadcast team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sescoops.com/taz-signs-multi-year-deal-with-aew/amp/|title=Taz Signs Multi-Year Deal With AEW|work=SEScoops.com|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling style and persona ==\nTazz's character was influenced by [[The Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]], [[The Steiner Brothers]] and [[Wild Samoans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-talks-early-disagreement-vince-mcmahon/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Talks About An Early Disagreement With Vince McMahon}}</ref> Tazz is nicknamed the \"Human Suplex Machine\" due to his wide array of suplex variations he would utilise in matches. His finishing move, the ''Tazmission'', is a half nelson choke with bodyscissors. He also sometimes combined this submission with a suplex, creating a half nelson choke suplex, called the ''Tazmission-Plex''.<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/the-50-coolest-maneuvers-of-all-time/page-16 |title=the 50 coolest maneuvers of all time|date=February 21, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014|publisher=WWE}}</ref> He has also claimed to have named the T-Bone Suplex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-says-named-t-bone-suplex/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Says He Named The T-Bone Suplex}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe has a [[tattoo]] of the [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Looney Tunes Tasmanian Devil]] on his upper right bicep accompanied by the legend Taz. His action figures produced by [[Jakks Pacific]] does not include the character, but does include the name. He has a self designed tattoo on his left lower bicep. Senerchia played [[Secondary school|high school]] [[high school football|football]]. Senerchia also studied [[judo]] prior to entering the professional wrestling circuit, reaching a second-degree black belt.<ref name=tazz73>Loverro, Thom (2006). ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]''. Pocket Books. {{ISBN|978-1-41-651312-4}}. p. 73</ref>  He is a fan of the [[New York Mets]], [[New York Knicks]], [[Philadelphia 76ers]], and the [[New York Jets]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==In other media==\nBeginning in 2018, Senercia was a nationally syndicated morning radio personality, co-hosting ''Taz and The Moose'' with Marc \"The Moose\" Malusis on [[CBS Sports Radio]] weekdays from 6-9 a.m. Eastern.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbssports.radio.com/shows/taz-and-moose|title=Taz & The Moose - CBS Sports Radio}}</ref> In December 2019, Senercia announced he was leaving the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://barrettsportsmedia.com/2019/12/17/taz-to-exit-cbs-sports-radio/|title=Taz To Exit CBS Sports Radio|date=2019-12-17|website=Barrett Sports Media|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>  \n\nSenercia also has his own podcast, called ''The Taz Show'', (formerly known as ''The Human Podcast Machine)'', where he discusses the latest in the professional wrestling world. The show has since discontinued. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.com/taz-show|title=The Taz Show|date=2018-04-30|website=RADIO.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nSenercia (as Tazz) appears as a playable character in ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007|SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]'' and ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009|SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n\n=== Amateur wrestling ===\n* Empire States Heavyweight Championship<ref>Noted by [[Joey Styles]] during the [[November to Remember 1997|1997 November to Remember]] broadcast</ref>\n\n=== Professional wrestling ===\n* '''[[Century Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n** [[CWA Cruiserweight Championship|CWA Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWA Cruiserweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"slambio\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/lhtcwa2.html|title=Solie's Title Histories: CWA - CENTURY WRESTLING ALLIANCE|website=www.solie.org}}</ref>\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern/Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=\"SolieFTW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Television Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Television Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/>\n** [[ECW World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|3 times]]) \u2013 with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]] (2)<sup>1</sup> and [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]] (1)<ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/>\n** Third [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of ECW Triple Crown Champions|ECW Triple Crown Champion]]\n* '''[[International World Class Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\"/>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 10 of the 500 best singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/1999.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 1999|accessdate=November 24, 2015|publisher=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him No. 147 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the \"[[PWI Years]]\" in 2003\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|3 times]])<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/hardcore-championship|title=Hardcore Championship|website=WWE}}</ref>\n** [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Spike Dudley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|title=World Tag Team Championship \u2013 Tazz & Spike Dudley|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024180601/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|archivedate=2012-10-24}}</ref>\n*'''''[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Gimmick|Worst Gimmick]] (2013) <small>[[Aces & Eights]]</small><ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=35}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (2013)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=26}}</ref>\n*'''Victory Championship Wrestling'''\n**VCW Hall of Fame (Class of 2018)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Peter Senerchia|Tazz}}\n* {{IMDb name|name = Peter Senerchia}}\n* {{WWE superstar|name = Tazz}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131103092937/http://www.impactwrestling.com/roster/Wrestler-Roster/item/1622-taz TNA profile]\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{Aces & Eights}}\n{{ECW Championship}}\n{{ECW World Television Championship}}\n{{ECW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n{{World Tag Team Championship (WWE)}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taz}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Aces and Eights members]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling personnel]]\n[[Category:American color commentators]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:ECW Heavyweight Champions/ECW World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Tag Team Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LIU Post alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:The Alliance (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:The Dangerous Alliance members]]\n[[Category:The ECW Originals members]]\n", "name_user": "KC Roosters", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"American radio personality, color commentator and professional wrestler\" to \"America professional wrestler, color commentator and radio personality\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tazz"}
{"title_page": "Leo Gibson", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Leo Gibson\n| image                = \"Leo Gibson (Minnesota Thunder) vs LA Galaxy.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| fullname             = Leo Gibson\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1983|8|9}}\n| birth_place          = [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]\n| height               = {{convert|1.68|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub          = [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]]\n| clubnumber           = 14\n| youthyears1          = 2000\u20132002\n| youthclubs1          = [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]]\n| collegeyears1          = 2002\u20132003\n| college1          = [[King Tornado]]\n| years1               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1               = [[Minnesota Thunder]]\n| caps1                = 48\n| goals1               = 9\n| years2               = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs2               = [[Detroit Ignition]] (indoor)\n| caps2                = 21\n| goals2               = 12\n| years3               = 2009\n| clubs3               = [[Cleveland City Stars]]\n| caps3                = 27\n| goals3               = 10\n| years4               = 2009\n| clubs4               = [[Rockford Rampage]] (indoor)\n| caps4                = 3\n| goals4               = 8\n| years5               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs5               = [[Philadelphia Kixx]] (indoor)\n| caps5                = 9\n| goals5               = 7\n| years6               = 2010\n| clubs6               = [[Charlotte Eagles]]\n| caps6                = 7\n| goals6               = 3\n| years7               = 2010\u2013\n| clubs7               = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (indoor)\n| caps7                = 203\n| goals7               = 251\n| nationalyears1       = \n| nationalteam1        = [[United States national futsal team|United States futsal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| nationalteam2        = [[United States national arena soccer team|United States arena soccer]]\n| manageryears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs1 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (asst.)\n| manageryears2 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs2 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = 7 April 2020\n| ntupdate             = July 6, 2014\n}}\n\n'''Leo Gibson''' (born August 9, 1983) is a [[Liberia]]n [[association football|soccer player]] who currently plays for and is the head coach for the [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]] in the [[Major Arena Soccer League|MASL]].<ref name=\"exmo150226\">{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Althaus |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Missouri)|The Examiner]] |publisher=[[GateHouse Media]] |location=[[Independence, MO]] |title=Not Missing the Point |url=http://www.examiner.net/article/20150226/SPORTS/150229155/0/SEARCH |date=February 26, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===College===\nGibson was born in [[Monrovia]], Liberia, but came to the United States in 2002, having previously played for the [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]] youth team in the [[Liberian Premier League]]. He played [[college soccer]] at [[King University|King College]] in Tennessee in 2002 and 2003.\n\n===Professional===\nGibson had a trial with the [[Dallas Burn]] of [[Major League Soccer]] in 2004.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |title=2004 Roster Dance |access-date=2008-08-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210084022/http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |archive-date=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> before eventually signing with the [[Minnesota Thunder]] of the [[USL First Division]] in 2005. However, a hand injury kept him from playing any games that season.<ref>[http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm Liberian forward Leo Gibson tries to replace Melvin Tarley with the Minnesota Thunder] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021060424/http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm |date=2008-10-21 }}</ref>  He remained with the Minnesota through the end of 2008, becoming an integral part of the team in the 2006 and 2007 seasons especially.\n\nIn 2007, the [[California Cougars]] of the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] selected Gibson with the 40th pick in the MISL Draft. He informed the team that he preferred to not play in California and the Cougars traded his rights to the [[Detroit Ignition]] on November 15, 2007 in exchange for a first round pick in the 2008 Supplemental Draft.<ref>[http://www.californiacougars.net/news/?id=641&cat=16 Cougars send Leo Gibson to Ignition for draft picks]</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2009, having been released by Minnesota, Gibson signed for the [[Cleveland City Stars]] for an undisclosed transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |title=Minnesota transfers Gibson to Cleveland |access-date=2009-04-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215162301/http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |archive-date=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played 27 games and scored 2 goals for Cleveland before the club folded at the end of the season; after a brief return to indoor soccer with [[Philadelphia Kixx]] in 2009\u201310, he signed with [[USL Second Division]] side [[Charlotte Eagles]] in 2010.\n\nGibson was signed to play in the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u2013)|MISL]]'s return to Kansas City with the [[Missouri Comets]] on October 16, 2010.  Named the MISL\u2019s Offensive Player of the Month in November, it was Gibson\u2019s move to the Comets\u2019 DEFENSIVE end on New Year\u2019s Eve that provided the club its much-needed spark in the back. Despite playing the first seven games on offense, Gibson still tied for the team lead in blocks with 20, which tied him for 6th overall in the league. Gibson was a tenacious defender, but he was often able to find the back of the net for the Comets, finishing 8th in the league in scoring with 45 points and finishing tied for the second most 3-point goals with four.  As a reward for his efforts, Gibson was named 1st Team All-MISL.\n\nGibson was named head coach of the Comets on October 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=COMETS SELECT SCORING LEADER FOR COACH |url=https://www.kccomets.com/news/comets-select-scoring-leader-for-coach |website=KCComets.com |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Honors===\n;Kansas City Comets\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u201314)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] Runners-Up: 2012-13 <ref>{{cite web |title=2012-13 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012%E2%80%9313_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u201314)|Major Indoor Soccer League]]: 2013-14 <ref>{{cite news |title=MISL: Missouri Comets claim first championship in dramatic win over Baltimore Blast |url=https://www.soccerwire.com/news/misl-missouri-comets-claim-first-championship-in-dramatic-win-over-baltimore-blast/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |agency=Soccer Wire |publisher=Hummer Sport |date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n;Individual\n*All-MISL First Team: 2010-11, 2012-13, 2013-14 <ref>{{cite web |title=2010-11 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010%E2%80%9311_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*All-MISL Second Team: 2011-12 <ref>{{cite web |title=2011-12 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011%E2%80%9312_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Major Arena Soccer League]] MVP: 2014-15\n*All-MASL First Team: 2014-15\n*All-MASL Second Team: 2015-16\n*All-MASL Third Team: 2017-18, 2018-19, 2019-20 <ref>{{cite web |title=Awards |url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/awards-2018-2019 |website=MASL |publisher=Soccer Shift |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Ed Tepper Humanitarian of the Year: 2017-18\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.clevelandcitystars.com/leo-gibson Cleveland City Stars bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071201120525/http://www.detroitignition.com/players/?id=26 Detroit Ignition bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080801171341/http://www.mnthunder.com/igsbase/igstemplate.cfm?SRC=MD008&SRCN=biodetail&GnavID=5&SnavID=73&TnavID=&StaffBioID=17 Minnesota Thunder bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Leo}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Detroit Ignition players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Liberian footballers]]\n[[Category:Liberian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008) players]]\n[[Category:Monrovia Black Star FC players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Thunder players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland City Stars players]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monrovia]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:USL Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Missouri Comets players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia KiXX (MISL) players]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u20132014) players]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's futsal players]]\n[[Category:Rockford Rampage players]]\n[[Category:Major Arena Soccer League coaches]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Leo Gibson\n| image                = \"Leo Gibson (Minnesota Thunder) vs LA Galaxy.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| fullname             = Leo Gibson\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1983|8|9}}\n| birth_place          = [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]\n| height               = {{convert|1.68|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub          = [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]]\n| clubnumber           = 14\n| youthyears1          = 2000\u20132002\n| youthclubs1          = [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]]\n| collegeyears1          = 2002\u20132003\n| college1          = [[King Tornado]]\n| years1               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1               = [[Minnesota Thunder]]\n| caps1                = 48\n| goals1               = 9\n| years2               = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs2               = [[Detroit Ignition]] (indoor)\n| caps2                = 21\n| goals2               = 12\n| years3               = 2009\n| clubs3               = [[Cleveland City Stars]]\n| caps3                = 27\n| goals3               = 10\n| years4               = 2009\n| clubs4               = [[Rockford Rampage]] (indoor)\n| caps4                = 3\n| goals4               = 8\n| years5               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs5               = [[Philadelphia Kixx]] (indoor)\n| caps5                = 9\n| goals5               = 7\n| years6               = 2010\n| clubs6               = [[Charlotte Eagles]]\n| caps6                = 7\n| goals6               = 3\n| years7               = 2010\u2013\n| clubs7               = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (indoor)\n| caps7                = 203\n| goals7               = 251\n| nationalyears1       = \n| nationalteam1        = [[United States national futsal team|United States futsal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| nationalteam2        = [[United States national arena soccer team|United States arena soccer]]\n| manageryears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs1 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (asst.)\n| manageryears2 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs2 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = 7 April 2020\n| ntupdate             = July 6, 2014\n}}\n\n'''Leo Gibson''' (born August 9, 1983) is a [[Liberia]]n [[association football|soccer player]] who currently plays for and is the head coach for the [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]] in the [[Major Arena Soccer League|MASL]].<ref name=\"exmo150226\">{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Althaus |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Missouri)|The Examiner]] |publisher=[[GateHouse Media]] |location=[[Independence, MO]] |title=Not Missing the Point |url=http://www.examiner.net/article/20150226/SPORTS/150229155/0/SEARCH |date=February 26, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===College===\nGibson was born in [[Monrovia]], Liberia, but came to the United States in 2002, having previously played for the [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]] youth team in the [[Liberian Premier League]]. He played [[college soccer]] at [[King University|King College]] in Tennessee in 2002 and 2003.\n\n===Professional===\nGibson had a trial with the [[Dallas Burn]] of [[Major League Soccer]] in 2004.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |title=2004 Roster Dance |access-date=2008-08-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210084022/http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |archive-date=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> before eventually signing with the [[Minnesota Thunder]] of the [[USL First Division]] in 2005. However, a hand injury kept him from playing any games that season.<ref>[http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm Liberian forward Leo Gibson tries to replace Melvin Tarley with the Minnesota Thunder] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021060424/http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm |date=2008-10-21 }}</ref>  He remained with the Minnesota through the end of 2008, becoming an integral part of the team in the 2006 and 2007 seasons especially.\n\nIn 2007, the [[California Cougars]] of the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] selected Gibson with the 40th pick in the MISL Draft. He informed the team that he preferred to not play in California and the Cougars traded his rights to the [[Detroit Ignition]] on November 15, 2007 in exchange for a first round pick in the 2008 Supplemental Draft.<ref>[http://www.californiacougars.net/news/?id=641&cat=16 Cougars send Leo Gibson to Ignition for draft picks]</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2009, having been released by Minnesota, Gibson signed for the [[Cleveland City Stars]] for an undisclosed transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |title=Minnesota transfers Gibson to Cleveland |access-date=2009-04-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215162301/http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |archive-date=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played 27 games and scored 2 goals for Cleveland before the club folded at the end of the season; after a brief return to indoor soccer with [[Philadelphia Kixx]] in 2009\u201310, he signed with [[USL Second Division]] side [[Charlotte Eagles]] in 2010.\n\nGibson was signed to play in the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u2013)|MISL]]'s return to Kansas City with the [[Missouri Comets]] on October 16, 2010.  Named the MISL\u2019s Offensive Player of the Month in November, it was Gibson\u2019s move to the Comets\u2019 DEFENSIVE end on New Year\u2019s Eve that provided the club its much-needed spark in the back. Despite playing the first seven games on offense, Gibson still tied for the team lead in blocks with 20, which tied him for 6th overall in the league. Gibson was a tenacious defender, but he was often able to find the back of the net for the Comets, finishing 8th in the league in scoring with 45 points and finishing tied for the second most 3-point goals with four.  As a reward for his efforts, Gibson was named 1st Team All-MISL.\n\nGibson was named head coach of the Comets on October 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=COMETS SELECT SCORING LEADER FOR COACH |url=https://www.kccomets.com/news/comets-select-scoring-leader-for-coach |website=KCComets.com |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Honors===\n;Kansas City Comets\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League]] Runners-Up: 2012-13 <ref>{{cite web |title=2012-13 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012%E2%80%9313_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League]]: 2013-14 <ref>{{cite news |title=MISL: Missouri Comets claim first championship in dramatic win over Baltimore Blast |url=https://www.soccerwire.com/news/misl-missouri-comets-claim-first-championship-in-dramatic-win-over-baltimore-blast/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |agency=Soccer Wire |publisher=Hummer Sport |date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n;Individual\n*All-MISL First Team: 2010-11, 2012-13, 2013-14 <ref>{{cite web |title=2010-11 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010%E2%80%9311_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*All-MISL Second Team: 2011-12 <ref>{{cite web |title=2011-12 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011%E2%80%9312_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Major Arena Soccer League]] MVP: 2014-15\n*All-MASL First Team: 2014-15\n*All-MASL Second Team: 2015-16\n*All-MASL Third Team: 2017-18, 2018-19, 2019-20 <ref>{{cite web |title=Awards |url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/awards-2018-2019 |website=MASL |publisher=Soccer Shift |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Ed Tepper Humanitarian of the Year: 2017-18\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.clevelandcitystars.com/leo-gibson Cleveland City Stars bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071201120525/http://www.detroitignition.com/players/?id=26 Detroit Ignition bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080801171341/http://www.mnthunder.com/igsbase/igstemplate.cfm?SRC=MD008&SRCN=biodetail&GnavID=5&SnavID=73&TnavID=&StaffBioID=17 Minnesota Thunder bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Leo}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Detroit Ignition players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Liberian footballers]]\n[[Category:Liberian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008) players]]\n[[Category:Monrovia Black Star FC players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Thunder players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland City Stars players]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monrovia]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:USL Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Missouri Comets players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia KiXX (MISL) players]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u20132014) players]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's futsal players]]\n[[Category:Rockford Rampage players]]\n[[Category:Major Arena Soccer League coaches]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMajor Indoor Soccer League(link changed toMajor Indoor Soccer League (2008\u201314); link changed toMajor Indoor Soccer League (2008\u201314)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Gibson"}
{"title_page": "Preki", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Preki\n| image       = PREKI.jpg\n| image_size  = 300\n| caption     = Preki in a press conference as head coach of [[Toronto FC]], 2010\n| fullname    = Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1963|6|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Belgrade]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| height      =\n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Seattle Sounders FC]] (assistant)\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[FK \u010cukari\u010dki Stankom|\u010cukari\u010dki Stankom]]\n| years1 = 1982\u20131985\n| clubs1 = [[Red Star Belgrade]]\n| caps1 = 2\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1985\u20131990\n| clubs2 = [[Tacoma Stars (MISL)|Tacoma Stars]] (indoor)\n| caps2 = 247\n| goals2 = 209\n| years3 = 1990\n| clubs3 = [[R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK]]\n| caps3 =\n| goals3 =\n| years4 = 1990\u20131992\n| clubs4 = [[St. Louis Storm]] (indoor)\n| caps4 = 91\n| goals4 = 113\n| years5 = 1992\u20131994\n| clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| caps5 = 46\n| goals5 = 4\n| years6 = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs6 = [[San Jose Grizzlies]] (indoor)\n| caps6 = 32\n| goals6 = 67\n| years7 = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs7 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| caps7 = 40\n| goals7 = 5\n| years8 = 1996\u20132000\n| clubs8 = [[Sporting Kansas City|Kansas City Wizards]]\n| caps8 = 145\n| goals8 = 50\n| years9 = 2001\n| clubs9 = [[Miami Fusion]]\n| caps9 = 24\n| goals9 = 8\n| years10 = 2002\u20132005\n| clubs10 = [[Kansas City Wizards]]\n| caps10 = 73\n| goals10 = 21\n| totalcaps = 330 \n| totalgoals = 88 \n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20132001\n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 28\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| manageryears1 = 2006\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chivas USA]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2007\u20132009\n| managerclubs2 = [[Chivas USA]]\n| manageryears3 = 2010\n| managerclubs3 = [[Toronto FC]]\n| manageryears4 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs4 = [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]]\n| manageryears5 = 2017\n| managerclubs5 = [[Saint Louis FC]]\n| manageryears6 = 2018\u2013\n| managerclubs6 = [[Seattle Sounders FC]] (assistant)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Country|{{Flagu|United States}}}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]|[[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1998]]}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Soccer]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0440\u0430\u0433 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b}}; born June 24, 1963), better known by the nickname '''Preki''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|r|\u025b|k|i}}), is a [[Serbian American|Serbian-American]] former [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. international]] [[association football|soccer]] manager. He previously managed [[Sacramento Republic FC]] and [[Saint Louis FC]] in the [[USL Championship|United Soccer League]].  He also previously coached in [[Major League Soccer]] with [[Toronto FC]] and [[Chivas USA]].\n\nDuring his playing career he played for English clubs [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], and was an 'MLS original' upon the formation of [[Major League Soccer]] in 1996, playing for the [[Kansas City Wizards]] (now known as Sporting Kansas City) and [[Miami Fusion]]. He is the only two-time winner of the MLS MVP award, now known as the [[Landon Donovan MVP Award]], and represented the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He was elected to the American [[National Soccer Hall of Fame]] in 2010.\n\nIn 2015 Preki left his managing role at [[Sacramento Republic FC]] by mutual consent. It was thought that he had landed the [[Leicester City FC]] job, but it was given to [[Claudio Ranieri]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/everton-fc-cult-figure-preki-9618350 |title=Everton FC cult figure Preki tipped for remarkable Premier League return |accessdate=2015-07-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304062130/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/everton-fc-cult-figure-preki-9618350 |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Professional===\nBorn in [[Socialist Republic of Serbia|Serbia]], Preki played briefly for [[Red Star Belgrade]] in the old [[Yugoslav First League]] after coming from [[FK \u010cukari\u010dki Stankom]] where he played in their youth team.<ref>[http://www.pageflip-flap.com/read?r=tOqdiQoYQtfej3f5jl Monografija: 85 godina SD \u010cukari\u010dki] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425080415/http://www.pageflip-flap.com/read?r=tOqdiQoYQtfej3f5jl |date=April 25, 2012 }} (page 91&92) {{in lang|sr}}</ref> In the summer of 1985, the [[Tacoma Stars (MISL)|Tacoma Stars]] head coach [[Bob McNab]] spotted Preki at an indoor tournament in [[Belgrade]]. McNab signed Preki.<ref>''`SECRET' SLAV ADDS SOCK TO STARS' SOCCER OFFENSE'' THE SEATTLE TIMES \u2013 Thursday, October 24, 1985</ref> He played five seasons for the Stars. During those years, he was a three-time First Team All Star, the 1988 and 1989 All Star Game MVP, led the league in assists in 1988 and scoring in 1989 and was the 1989 MISL MVP. During the summer of 1989, Preki began to consider becoming a U.S. citizen and returning to the outdoor game in order to make himself eligible for the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. national team]].<ref>''PREKI EYES RAISE, U.S. CITIZENSHIP \u2013 WORLD CUP BERTH IN MIND'' Seattle Post-Intelligencer \u2013 Wednesday, September 13, 1989</ref> He played one season for [[R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK]] in Sweden in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.raslattsk.se/03Historia.aspx |title= R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK \u2013 Historia |format= |work= |accessdate=January 25, 2011}}</ref> The Stars released Preki in July 1990 as part of a salary reduction move.<ref>''Tacoma cuts Preki, 5 more to pare costs'' San Diego Union (CA) \u2013 Thursday, July 5, 1990</ref> In August, he signed with the [[St. Louis Storm]].<ref>''STARS' PREKI SIGNS WITH ST. LOUIS'' THE SEATTLE TIMES \u2013 Monday, August 13, 1990</ref> He played two seasons in St. Louis before being bought by [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] manager [[Howard Kendall]] for a fee of \u00a3100,000 in the summer of 1992 following a trial. He made 53 appearances for the Blues, 28 of those as a substitute. In June 1994, Preki signed with the [[San Jose Grizzlies]] of the [[Continental Indoor Soccer League]] where he rejoined Bob McNab from his Tacoma days.<ref>''CONTINENTAL INDOOR SOCCER LEAGUE'' USA TODAY (Arlington, VA) \u2013 Tuesday, June 7, 1994</ref> He played eight games, scoring sixteen goals, before returning to England in August 1994 to play for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. On July 5, 1995, the Grizzlies purchased Preki's contract from Portsmouth.<ref>''GRIZZLIES ACQUIRE TOP INDOOR PLAYER'' San Jose Mercury News (CA) \u2013 Thursday, July 6, 1995</ref> He was the CISL's second leading scorer and league MVP.<ref>[http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1995.html#CISL The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1995] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226150651/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1995.html |date=February 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Major League Soccer===\nPreki resumed outdoor play beginning with MLS's inaugural season in 1996 when he joined the [[Kansas City Wiz]], renamed the Wizards after the 1996 season. The league [[1996 MLS Inaugural Allocations#Kansas City Wiz|allocated]] him to the Wiz on February 6, 1996.<ref>''Transactions'' The Kansas City Star \u2013 Tuesday, February 6, 1996</ref> He played every season of his MLS playing career for the Wizards, except for one season with the [[Miami Fusion]] in 2001. After the Fusion were contracted, the Wizards reacquired Preki in the [[2002 MLS Dispersal Draft]], but only after every other team in the league had passed on selecting him. Preki is the only player to have won the [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|MLS MVP Award]] and the [[MLS Golden Boot|MLS Scoring Champion Award]] (now respectively known as the Landon Donovan MVP Award and the MLS Golden Boot) twice, winning in 1997 and 2003, and is also the current all-time league leader in points scored (270 on 79 goals and 112 assists, plus another 25 points on 10 goals and 5 assists in the playoffs). He won the 2000 [[MLS Cup]] with the Wizards. Preki retired following the 2005 season, scoring a goal in the last minute of his final game with Kansas City. He was named to the [[MLS All-Time Best XI]] after the season, and was 42 years old when he played his final competitive game.<ref>[http://web.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=mls&player=radosavljevic_p&playerId=rad474619&statType=career MLS Player Stats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501181728/http://web.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=mls&player=radosavljevic_p&playerId=rad474619&statType=career |date=May 1, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===International===\nOriginally from Yugoslavia, Preki was living and working in the US in 1985 but when he was offered a spot on the [[United States men's national soccer team|American national team]] he applied for U.S. citizenship which was granted on October 25, 1996.<ref>https://ussoccerplayers.com/player/preki</ref> He made his debut for the United States on November 3, 1996 against [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] at the age of 33, making him one of the oldest players to make an international debut. Preki played a total of 28 games for the U.S., scoring four goals, one of them to beat [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1998 Gold Cup]]. Two of those games, including one against his native [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Yugoslavia]] (now [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]]), came in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He made his last appearance for the national team in a 2\u20130 loss away to Costa Rica in World Cup qualifying on September 5, 2001.<ref>[http://web.mlsnet.com/t120/load.jsp?section=about&content=coaches About Coaches: Preki Radosavljevic, Head Coach] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522013613/http://web.mlsnet.com/t120/load.jsp?section=about&content=coaches |date=May 22, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible expanded\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || December 21, 1996 || [[San Salvador]], El Salvador || {{fb|GUA}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 2\u20132 || [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup Qualifying]]\n|-\n| 2 || November 16, 1997 || [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]] || {{fb|SLV}} || '''4'''\u20132 || 4-2 || [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup Qualifying]]\n|-\n| 3 || February 7, 1998 || [[Oakland, California]] || {{fb|CRC}} || '''2'''\u20131 || 2\u20131 || [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|-\n| 4 || February 10, 1998 || [[Los Angeles, California]] || {{fb|BRA}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|}\n\n==Coaching career==\nUpon the appointment of [[Bob Bradley]] as the United States national team manager, Preki was promoted as head coach of Chivas USA for the 2007 [[Major League Soccer]] season.<ref name=hiredatchivas>{{cite news|title=Preki replaces Bradley as Chivas USA coach|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=400382&cc=5901|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=ESPN Soccernet|date=January 17, 2007|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nPreki left Chivas \"by mutual consent\" on November 12, 2009, following Chivas' failure to progress to the latter stages of the MLS playoffs.<ref name=departfromchivas>{{cite news|title=Chivas USA, Preki part ways|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=697912&sec=mls&cc=5901|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=ESPN Soccernet|date=November 12, 2009}}</ref> He became head coach of [[Toronto FC]] on November 19, 2009.<ref name=hiredbytoronto>[http://www.torontosun.com/sports/soccer/2009/11/19/11804886-sun.html TFC set to name Preki new head coach]</ref> However, Preki didn't last the 2010 MLS season with Toronto, being fired along with General Manager [[Mo Johnston]] on September 14, 2010.<ref name=firedbytoronto>{{cite news|last=Wolstat|first=Ryan|title=Axed TFC coach Preki fires back|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/soccer/2010/09/15/15366226.html|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=September 15, 2010|agency=QMI Agency}}</ref> Under Preki, Toronto qualified for the [[2010-11 CONCACAF Champions League]] after winning the [[2010 Canadian Championship]].\n\nOn July 15, 2013, after nearly three years out of coaching, Preki was named head coach of the [[United Soccer League|USL Professional Division]] (now United Soccer League) expansion [[Sacramento Republic FC]] in advance of their inaugural 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insider.sacprosoccer.com/page/press-release |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609190442/http://insider.sacprosoccer.com/page/press-release |archivedate=June 9, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He won the USL Pro Championship game in September 2014 with the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Republic FC Claims USL PRO Championship|url=http://uslpro.uslsoccer.com/home/839638.html|publisher=USL Pro|accessdate=September 28, 2014|date=September 27, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018101005/http://uslpro.uslsoccer.com/home/839638.html|archivedate=October 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 8, 2015, Preki announced his resignation from his post to take up a coaching role in the United Kingdom.\n\nOn October 12, 2016, USL club [[Saint Louis FC]] introduced Preki as its coach for the upcoming 2017 season. On November 20, 2017, [[Saint Louis FC]] relieved Preki of his coaching duties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lyons |first=Joe |date=October 12, 2016 |title=St. Louis FC introduces Preki as its new coach |url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/soccer/st-louis-fc-introduces-preki-as-its-new-coach/article_4f0433b9-e844-586a-ae10-ef6a4470fa5c.html |newspaper=Saint Louis Post-Dispatch |location=Saint Louis, Missouri |access-date=December 11, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118010559/http://www.stltoday.com/sports/soccer/st-louis-fc-introduces-preki-as-its-new-coach/article_4f0433b9-e844-586a-ae10-ef6a4470fa5c.html |archivedate=November 18, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Preki was hired as an assistant coach to [[Brian Schmetzer]] with the [[Seattle Sounders]].\n\n==Coaching record==\n\n{{updated|November 19, 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"| From\n!rowspan=\"2\"| To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n|-\n!G\n!W\n!L\n!T\n!GF\n!GA\n!GD\n!Win %\n|-\n| [[Chivas USA]]\n|January 17, 2007<ref name=hiredatchivas/>\n| November 12, 2009<ref name=departfromchivas/>\n{{WDL|107|41|36|30|for=132|against=125|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Toronto FC]]\n| November 19, 2009<ref name=hiredbytoronto/>\n| September 14, 2010<ref name=firedbytoronto/>\n{{WDL|32|11|11|10|for=30|against=31|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]]\n| July 15, 2013\n| July 8, 2015\n{{WDL|53|33|15|5|for=108|against=60|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Saint Louis FC]]\n| October 12, 2016\n| November 19, 2017\n{{WDL|35|11|15|9|for=41|against=53|diff=yes}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| Total\n{{WDLtot|227|96|77|54|for=311|against=269|diff=yes}}\n|}\n\n=='''Awards'''==\n===Club===\n;[[Tacoma Stars]]\n[[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u201392)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] Runners-Up: 1986-87\n;[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n*[[MLS Cup]]: 2000 <ref>{{cite web |title=2000 MLS Cup |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/history/2000-mls-cup |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Supporters' Shield]]: 2000 <ref>{{cite web |title=Supporters' Shield |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supporters%27_Shield |website=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[US Open Cup]]: 2004 <ref>{{cite web |title=2004 U.S. Open Cup |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/history/2004-open-cup |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Individual==\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u201392)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] MVP: 1988-89<ref>{{cite web |title=Major Indoor Soccer League |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_(1978%E2%80%931992)#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u201392)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] Scoring Champion: 1988-89 <ref>{{cite web |title=Major Arena Soccer League |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_(1978%E2%80%931992)#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia}}</ref>\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u201392)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] Pass Master (Most Assists): 1987-88, 1988-89 <ref>{{cite web |title=Major Arena Soccer League |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_(1978%E2%80%931992)#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1989 Major Indoor Soccer League All-Star Game]] MVP: 1989 <ref>{{cite web |title=1989 Major Indoor Soccer League All-Star Game |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_All-Star_Game |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Landon Donovan MVP Award]](2): 1997, 2003 <ref>{{cite web |title=Sporting Legends- Preki |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/sportinglegends/preki |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[MLS Golden Boot]]: 1997, 2003 <ref>{{cite web |title=MLS Golden Boot |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Golden_Boot |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[National Soccer Hall of Fame]]: Class of 2010 <ref>{{cite web |title=PREKI RADOSAVLJEVI\u00c4 |url=https://www.nationalsoccerhof.com/players/preki-radosavljevi%C3%A4%E2%80%A1.html |website=National Soccer Hall of Fame |publisher=U.S. Soccer |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Indoor Soccer Hall of Fame: Class of 2013 <ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Famers |url=https://www.indoorsoccerhall.com/hall-of-famers |website=Indoor Soccer Hall of Fame |publisher=Soccer Shift |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Preki}}\n* [http://www.ussoccerplayers.com/players/preki/ Preki profile at United States National Soccer Players]\n* [http://www.nasljerseys.com/MISL/Players/P/Preki.htm MISL stats]\n* {{NFT player|id=11454}}\n\n{{Seattle Sounders FC squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = United States squads\n| bg          = white\n| fg          = #002868\n| bordercolor = #BF0A30\n| list1 =\n{{United States squad 1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{United States squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{MLS All-Star Game MVP}}\n{{Major League Soccer MVP Award}}\n{{2003 MLS Best XI}}\n{{MLS Coach of the Year}}\n{{MLSXI}}\n{{National Soccer Hall of Fame members}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Managerial positions\n|list1 =\n{{Chivas USA managers}}\n{{Toronto FC managers}}\n{{Saint Louis FC coaches}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Preki}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Serbian footballers]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Red Star Belgrade footballers]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Stars players]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Storm players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:San Jose Grizzlies players]]\n[[Category:Portsmouth F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Miami Fusion players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (1978\u20131992) players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Continental Indoor Soccer League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer MVPs]]\n[[Category:United States men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:National Soccer Hall of Fame members]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:American expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Serbian football managers]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA coaches]]\n[[Category:Toronto FC coaches]]\n[[Category:Sacramento Republic FC coaches]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis FC coaches]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders FC non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:USL Championship coaches]]\n[[Category:Serbian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:American expatriate soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Canada]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer managers in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Preki\n| image       = PREKI.jpg\n| image_size  = 300\n| caption     = Preki in a press conference as head coach of [[Toronto FC]], 2010\n| fullname    = Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1963|6|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Belgrade]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| height      =\n| position    = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Seattle Sounders FC]] (assistant)\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[FK \u010cukari\u010dki Stankom|\u010cukari\u010dki Stankom]]\n| years1 = 1982\u20131985\n| clubs1 = [[Red Star Belgrade]]\n| caps1 = 2\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1985\u20131990\n| clubs2 = [[Tacoma Stars (MISL)|Tacoma Stars]] (indoor)\n| caps2 = 247\n| goals2 = 209\n| years3 = 1990\n| clubs3 = [[R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK]]\n| caps3 =\n| goals3 =\n| years4 = 1990\u20131992\n| clubs4 = [[St. Louis Storm]] (indoor)\n| caps4 = 91\n| goals4 = 113\n| years5 = 1992\u20131994\n| clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| caps5 = 46\n| goals5 = 4\n| years6 = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs6 = [[San Jose Grizzlies]] (indoor)\n| caps6 = 32\n| goals6 = 67\n| years7 = 1994\u20131995\n| clubs7 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| caps7 = 40\n| goals7 = 5\n| years8 = 1996\u20132000\n| clubs8 = [[Sporting Kansas City|Kansas City Wizards]]\n| caps8 = 145\n| goals8 = 50\n| years9 = 2001\n| clubs9 = [[Miami Fusion]]\n| caps9 = 24\n| goals9 = 8\n| years10 = 2002\u20132005\n| clubs10 = [[Kansas City Wizards]]\n| caps10 = 73\n| goals10 = 21\n| totalcaps = 330 \n| totalgoals = 88 \n| nationalyears1 = 1996\u20132001\n| nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 28\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| manageryears1 = 2006\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chivas USA]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2007\u20132009\n| managerclubs2 = [[Chivas USA]]\n| manageryears3 = 2010\n| managerclubs3 = [[Toronto FC]]\n| manageryears4 = 2014\u20132015\n| managerclubs4 = [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]]\n| manageryears5 = 2017\n| managerclubs5 = [[Saint Louis FC]]\n| manageryears6 = 2018\u2013\n| managerclubs6 = [[Seattle Sounders FC]] (assistant)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Country|{{Flagu|United States}}}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]|[[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1998]]}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|Soccer]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-Cyrl|\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0440\u0430\u0433 \u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b}}; born June 24, 1963), better known by the nickname '''Preki''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|r|\u025b|k|i}}), is a [[Serbian American|Serbian-American]] former [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. international]] [[association football|soccer]] manager. He previously managed [[Sacramento Republic FC]] and [[Saint Louis FC]] in the [[USL Championship|United Soccer League]].  He also previously coached in [[Major League Soccer]] with [[Toronto FC]] and [[Chivas USA]].\n\nDuring his playing career he played for English clubs [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], and was an 'MLS original' upon the formation of [[Major League Soccer]] in 1996, playing for the [[Kansas City Wizards]] (now known as Sporting Kansas City) and [[Miami Fusion]]. He is the only two-time winner of the MLS MVP award, now known as the [[Landon Donovan MVP Award]], and represented the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He was elected to the American [[National Soccer Hall of Fame]] in 2010.\n\nIn 2015 Preki left his managing role at [[Sacramento Republic FC]] by mutual consent. It was thought that he had landed the [[Leicester City FC]] job, but it was given to [[Claudio Ranieri]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/everton-fc-cult-figure-preki-9618350 |title=Everton FC cult figure Preki tipped for remarkable Premier League return |accessdate=2015-07-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304062130/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/everton-fc-cult-figure-preki-9618350 |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Professional===\nBorn in [[Socialist Republic of Serbia|Serbia]], Preki played briefly for [[Red Star Belgrade]] in the old [[Yugoslav First League]] after coming from [[FK \u010cukari\u010dki Stankom]] where he played in their youth team.<ref>[http://www.pageflip-flap.com/read?r=tOqdiQoYQtfej3f5jl Monografija: 85 godina SD \u010cukari\u010dki] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425080415/http://www.pageflip-flap.com/read?r=tOqdiQoYQtfej3f5jl |date=April 25, 2012 }} (page 91&92) {{in lang|sr}}</ref> In the summer of 1985, the [[Tacoma Stars (MISL)|Tacoma Stars]] head coach [[Bob McNab]] spotted Preki at an indoor tournament in [[Belgrade]]. McNab signed Preki.<ref>''`SECRET' SLAV ADDS SOCK TO STARS' SOCCER OFFENSE'' THE SEATTLE TIMES \u2013 Thursday, October 24, 1985</ref> He played five seasons for the Stars. During those years, he was a three-time First Team All Star, the 1988 and 1989 All Star Game MVP, led the league in assists in 1988 and scoring in 1989 and was the 1989 MISL MVP. During the summer of 1989, Preki began to consider becoming a U.S. citizen and returning to the outdoor game in order to make himself eligible for the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. national team]].<ref>''PREKI EYES RAISE, U.S. CITIZENSHIP \u2013 WORLD CUP BERTH IN MIND'' Seattle Post-Intelligencer \u2013 Wednesday, September 13, 1989</ref> He played one season for [[R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK]] in Sweden in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.raslattsk.se/03Historia.aspx |title= R\u00e5sl\u00e4tts SK \u2013 Historia |format= |work= |accessdate=January 25, 2011}}</ref> The Stars released Preki in July 1990 as part of a salary reduction move.<ref>''Tacoma cuts Preki, 5 more to pare costs'' San Diego Union (CA) \u2013 Thursday, July 5, 1990</ref> In August, he signed with the [[St. Louis Storm]].<ref>''STARS' PREKI SIGNS WITH ST. LOUIS'' THE SEATTLE TIMES \u2013 Monday, August 13, 1990</ref> He played two seasons in St. Louis before being bought by [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] manager [[Howard Kendall]] for a fee of \u00a3100,000 in the summer of 1992 following a trial. He made 53 appearances for the Blues, 28 of those as a substitute. In June 1994, Preki signed with the [[San Jose Grizzlies]] of the [[Continental Indoor Soccer League]] where he rejoined Bob McNab from his Tacoma days.<ref>''CONTINENTAL INDOOR SOCCER LEAGUE'' USA TODAY (Arlington, VA) \u2013 Tuesday, June 7, 1994</ref> He played eight games, scoring sixteen goals, before returning to England in August 1994 to play for [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. On July 5, 1995, the Grizzlies purchased Preki's contract from Portsmouth.<ref>''GRIZZLIES ACQUIRE TOP INDOOR PLAYER'' San Jose Mercury News (CA) \u2013 Thursday, July 6, 1995</ref> He was the CISL's second leading scorer and league MVP.<ref>[http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1995.html#CISL The Year in American Soccer \u2013 1995] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226150651/http://homepages.sover.net/~spectrum/year/1995.html |date=February 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Major League Soccer===\nPreki resumed outdoor play beginning with MLS's inaugural season in 1996 when he joined the [[Kansas City Wiz]], renamed the Wizards after the 1996 season. The league [[1996 MLS Inaugural Allocations#Kansas City Wiz|allocated]] him to the Wiz on February 6, 1996.<ref>''Transactions'' The Kansas City Star \u2013 Tuesday, February 6, 1996</ref> He played every season of his MLS playing career for the Wizards, except for one season with the [[Miami Fusion]] in 2001. After the Fusion were contracted, the Wizards reacquired Preki in the [[2002 MLS Dispersal Draft]], but only after every other team in the league had passed on selecting him. Preki is the only player to have won the [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|MLS MVP Award]] and the [[MLS Golden Boot|MLS Scoring Champion Award]] (now respectively known as the Landon Donovan MVP Award and the MLS Golden Boot) twice, winning in 1997 and 2003, and is also the current all-time league leader in points scored (270 on 79 goals and 112 assists, plus another 25 points on 10 goals and 5 assists in the playoffs). He won the 2000 [[MLS Cup]] with the Wizards. Preki retired following the 2005 season, scoring a goal in the last minute of his final game with Kansas City. He was named to the [[MLS All-Time Best XI]] after the season, and was 42 years old when he played his final competitive game.<ref>[http://web.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=mls&player=radosavljevic_p&playerId=rad474619&statType=career MLS Player Stats] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501181728/http://web.mlsnet.com/players/bio.jsp?team=mls&player=radosavljevic_p&playerId=rad474619&statType=career |date=May 1, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===International===\nOriginally from Yugoslavia, Preki was living and working in the US in 1985 but when he was offered a spot on the [[United States men's national soccer team|American national team]] he applied for U.S. citizenship which was granted on October 25, 1996.<ref>https://ussoccerplayers.com/player/preki</ref> He made his debut for the United States on November 3, 1996 against [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] at the age of 33, making him one of the oldest players to make an international debut. Preki played a total of 28 games for the U.S., scoring four goals, one of them to beat [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup|1998 Gold Cup]]. Two of those games, including one against his native [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Yugoslavia]] (now [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]]), came in the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He made his last appearance for the national team in a 2\u20130 loss away to Costa Rica in World Cup qualifying on September 5, 2001.<ref>[http://web.mlsnet.com/t120/load.jsp?section=about&content=coaches About Coaches: Preki Radosavljevic, Head Coach] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522013613/http://web.mlsnet.com/t120/load.jsp?section=about&content=coaches |date=May 22, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible expanded\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1 || December 21, 1996 || [[San Salvador]], El Salvador || {{fb|GUA}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 2\u20132 || [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup Qualifying]]\n|-\n| 2 || November 16, 1997 || [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]] || {{fb|SLV}} || '''4'''\u20132 || 4-2 || [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|1998 World Cup Qualifying]]\n|-\n| 3 || February 7, 1998 || [[Oakland, California]] || {{fb|CRC}} || '''2'''\u20131 || 2\u20131 || [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|-\n| 4 || February 10, 1998 || [[Los Angeles, California]] || {{fb|BRA}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[1998 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|}\n\n==Coaching career==\nUpon the appointment of [[Bob Bradley]] as the United States national team manager, Preki was promoted as head coach of Chivas USA for the 2007 [[Major League Soccer]] season.<ref name=hiredatchivas>{{cite news|title=Preki replaces Bradley as Chivas USA coach|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=400382&cc=5901|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=ESPN Soccernet|date=January 17, 2007|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nPreki left Chivas \"by mutual consent\" on November 12, 2009, following Chivas' failure to progress to the latter stages of the MLS playoffs.<ref name=departfromchivas>{{cite news|title=Chivas USA, Preki part ways|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=697912&sec=mls&cc=5901|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=ESPN Soccernet|date=November 12, 2009}}</ref> He became head coach of [[Toronto FC]] on November 19, 2009.<ref name=hiredbytoronto>[http://www.torontosun.com/sports/soccer/2009/11/19/11804886-sun.html TFC set to name Preki new head coach]</ref> However, Preki didn't last the 2010 MLS season with Toronto, being fired along with General Manager [[Mo Johnston]] on September 14, 2010.<ref name=firedbytoronto>{{cite news|last=Wolstat|first=Ryan|title=Axed TFC coach Preki fires back|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/soccer/2010/09/15/15366226.html|accessdate=January 14, 2013|newspaper=Toronto Sun|date=September 15, 2010|agency=QMI Agency}}</ref> Under Preki, Toronto qualified for the [[2010-11 CONCACAF Champions League]] after winning the [[2010 Canadian Championship]].\n\nOn July 15, 2013, after nearly three years out of coaching, Preki was named head coach of the [[United Soccer League|USL Professional Division]] (now United Soccer League) expansion [[Sacramento Republic FC]] in advance of their inaugural 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insider.sacprosoccer.com/page/press-release |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609190442/http://insider.sacprosoccer.com/page/press-release |archivedate=June 9, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He won the USL Pro Championship game in September 2014 with the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Republic FC Claims USL PRO Championship|url=http://uslpro.uslsoccer.com/home/839638.html|publisher=USL Pro|accessdate=September 28, 2014|date=September 27, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018101005/http://uslpro.uslsoccer.com/home/839638.html|archivedate=October 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On July 8, 2015, Preki announced his resignation from his post to take up a coaching role in the United Kingdom.\n\nOn October 12, 2016, USL club [[Saint Louis FC]] introduced Preki as its coach for the upcoming 2017 season. On November 20, 2017, [[Saint Louis FC]] relieved Preki of his coaching duties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lyons |first=Joe |date=October 12, 2016 |title=St. Louis FC introduces Preki as its new coach |url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/soccer/st-louis-fc-introduces-preki-as-its-new-coach/article_4f0433b9-e844-586a-ae10-ef6a4470fa5c.html |newspaper=Saint Louis Post-Dispatch |location=Saint Louis, Missouri |access-date=December 11, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118010559/http://www.stltoday.com/sports/soccer/st-louis-fc-introduces-preki-as-its-new-coach/article_4f0433b9-e844-586a-ae10-ef6a4470fa5c.html |archivedate=November 18, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Preki was hired as an assistant coach to [[Brian Schmetzer]] with the [[Seattle Sounders]].\n\n==Coaching record==\n\n{{updated|November 19, 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"| From\n!rowspan=\"2\"| To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\n|-\n!G\n!W\n!L\n!T\n!GF\n!GA\n!GD\n!Win %\n|-\n| [[Chivas USA]]\n|January 17, 2007<ref name=hiredatchivas/>\n| November 12, 2009<ref name=departfromchivas/>\n{{WDL|107|41|36|30|for=132|against=125|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Toronto FC]]\n| November 19, 2009<ref name=hiredbytoronto/>\n| September 14, 2010<ref name=firedbytoronto/>\n{{WDL|32|11|11|10|for=30|against=31|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]]\n| July 15, 2013\n| July 8, 2015\n{{WDL|53|33|15|5|for=108|against=60|diff=yes}}\n|-\n| [[Saint Louis FC]]\n| October 12, 2016\n| November 19, 2017\n{{WDL|35|11|15|9|for=41|against=53|diff=yes}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"| Total\n{{WDLtot|227|96|77|54|for=311|against=269|diff=yes}}\n|}\n\n=='''Awards'''==\n===Club===\n;[[Tacoma Stars]]\n[[Major Indoor Soccer League]] Runners-Up: 1986-87\n;[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n*[[MLS Cup]]: 2000 <ref>{{cite web |title=2000 MLS Cup |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/history/2000-mls-cup |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Supporters' Shield]]: 2000 <ref>{{cite web |title=Supporters' Shield |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supporters%27_Shield |website=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[US Open Cup]]: 2004 <ref>{{cite web |title=2004 U.S. Open Cup |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/history/2004-open-cup |