= \n| diocese                = [[Anglican Diocese of Canberra and Goulburn|Canberra and Goulburn]]\n| province               = \n| presbytery             = \n| synod                  = \n| circuit                = \n| district               = \n| division               = \n| subdivision            =\n\n| archbishop             = \n| bishop                 = \n| auxiliary bishop       =\n| cardinal protector     =\n| abbot                  = \n| prior                  = \n| subprior               = \n| exarch                 = \n| provost-rector         = \n| provost                = \n| viceprovost            = \n| rector                 = Paul Black\n| vicar                  = \n| dean                   = \n| subdean                = \n| archpriest             = \n| precentor              = \n| succentor              = \n| chancellor             = \n| canonchancellor        = \n| canon                  = \n| canonpastor            =\n| canonmissioner         = \n| canontreasurer         = \n| prebendary             = \n| priestincharge         = \n| priest                 = \n| asstpriest             = Margaret Emil, Kevin Stone\n| honpriest              =\n| curate                 = \n| asstcurate             = \n| nonstipendiaryminister =\n| minister               = \n| assistant              = \n| seniorpastor           = \n| pastor                 = \n| chaplain               = \n| archdeacon             = \n| deacon                 = \n| deaconess              =\n\n| reader                 = \n| student intern         = \n| organistdom            = Sheila Thompson OAM\n| director               = \n| organist               =\n| organscholar           = \n| chapterclerk           = \n| laychapter             = \n| warden                 = \n| verger                 = \n| businessmgr            = \n| liturgycoord           = \n| reledu                 = \n| rcia                   = \n| youthmin               = \n| flowerguild            = \n| musicgroup             = St John's Choir\n| parishadmin            = \n| serversguild           = \n| sacristan              = Margaret Rodgers\n\n| logo                   = \n| logosize               = \n| logolink               = \n| logoalt                =\n\n| embedded               = \n}}\n'''St John the Baptist Church''' is an Australian [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican]] [[Church (building)|church]] in the [[Canberra]] suburb of [[Reid, Australian Capital Territory|Reid]] in the [[Australian Capital Territory]]. The church is located at the corner of [[Anzac Parade, Canberra|Anzac Parade]] and Constitution Avenue, adjacent to the [[Parliamentary Triangle, Canberra|Parliamentary Triangle]], and is the oldest surviving public building within Canberra's inner city and the oldest church in the Australian Capital Territory.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Randall |title=Sanctuary in the city : the Anglican Church of St John the Baptist Canberra |date=2012 |publisher=The Anglican Church of St John the Baptist, Canberra |isbn=9780646574455}}</ref> It has been described as a \"sanctuary in the city\",<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Randall |title=Sanctuary in the city : the Anglican Church of St John the Baptist Canberra |date=2012 |publisher=The Anglican Church of St John the Baptist, Canberra |isbn=9780646574455}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sanctuary in the City |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/sanctuary-in-the-city |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> remaining a small English village-style church even as Australia's capital grew around it. Over time, it became a focal point for Australia's governors-general, politicians, public servants and military leaders,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Allbrook |first1=Malcolm |title=History of Canberra's oldest church |journal=Australian National University Reporter |date=2015 |volume=46 |issue=2}}</ref> and has hosted royalty on numerous occasions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Royalty Attends Wedding |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ppLYo4Z3XBo |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=British Pathe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Queen meets Rush, attends church service |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-10-23/queen-to-host-luncheon-at-government-house/3595662 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe church remains an active place of worship and a Canberra landmark, although it has now been surrounded by offices and residential buildings. The bells of St John's, cast from the same foundry as the National Carillon,<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bells of St John's |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/the-bells |publisher=St John's Canberra |date= |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=National Carillon |url=https://www.nca.gov.au/carillon |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> are audible from [[Lake Burley Griffin]]. St John's Care, a local charity, emergency relief and community organisation affiliated with [[Anglicare]],<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Care |url=https://www.stjohnscare.org.au/ |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> is based in the church precinct, as is the parish's musical group, the St John's Choir.<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Choir |url=http://www.stjohnschoir.org/ |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> An annual community fair has been held in the church grounds since the 1930s, with participation from local schools, bands and arts organisations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fair |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/fair |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> In March 2020, the church celebrated its 175th anniversary since its consecration in 1845.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref> \n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Exterior of St John the Baptist Church Reid April 2017.jpg|thumb|left|West facade with tower]]\n[[File:Church_of_St_Johns_Canberra-01%2B_(448617320).jpg|thumb|left|East facade with the east window]]\nSt John's is oriented east-west, with the nave to the east and the main entrance (with [[choir]] [[loft]] and [[Organ (music)|organ]] above) to the west. The site was chosen by [[Robert Campbell (Australian landowner)|Robert Campbell]] in 1840, with the support of [[William Grant Broughton]], the first and only Bishop of Australia.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref> Campbell was a Presbyterian but became a generous benefactors of Anglican activity in New South Wales, and Bishop Broughton tried to entrench the then Church of England in Australia as \"the national church, established in law, charged with the care of all subjects of the Crown, apostolic in its doctrine and government\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Allbrook |first1=Malcolm |title=History of Canberra's oldest church |journal=Australian National University Reporter |date=2015 |volume=46 |issue=2}}</ref> St John's was a product of these efforts. The foundation stone was laid in on 11 May 1841 by the Revd Edward Smith, Rector of Queanbeyan, and the church was consecrated on 12 March 1845 by Bishop Broughton.<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a step back in time and get in touch with Canberra's early history |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe building  was constructed over a period of several years and was completed in three stages in the Victorian Free Medieval and [[Australian non-residential architectural styles#Victorian Ecclesiastical Gothic|Victorian Gothic Revival]] styles:<ref name=\"Body\">{{Cite book |last=Body |first=A. H. |title=Firm Still You Stand |publisher=St John's Parish Council |year=1986 }}</ref>\n\n*The original church erected by [[Robert Campbell (Australian landowner)|Robert Campbell]] (1841\u201345)\n*[[Nave]] extension by George Campbell\n*[[Chancel]] by John Campbell (1872\u201373)\n\nSandstone for the church was sourced from quarries located at the base of Black Mountain and Quarry Hill (located in the suburb of [[Yarralumla, Australian Capital Territory|Yarralumla]]).<ref>{{cite book |author=Robinson F. W. |year=1924 |title=Canberra's First Hundred Years |publisher=WC Penfold & Co Limited |isbn= |page= }}</ref> \n\nThe original {{convert|20|ft|m|0|order=flip|adj=on}} church tower was erected in 1845 but developed a {{convert|2|ft|m|0|order=flip|adj=on|spell=on}} lean, was deemed unsafe and was dismantled in 1864. The present tower was designed by [[Edmund Blacket]] and erected during the period 1865\u20131870. Sandstone for the tower\u2019s window mouldings was hauled by bullock from the Camden-Bargo district, a distance of {{convert|100|mi|km|0|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"Body\"/> The spire was completed in 1877 and together with the trees surrounding the church, became a prominent landmark in Canberra\u2019s early years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a step back in time and get in touch with Canberra's early history |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe church and associated schoolhouse museum were added to the (now defunct) Australian [[Register of the National Estate]] on 21 October 1980.<ref>{{cite AHD|13265|St Johns Church and Churchyard, 1 Anzac Park West, Reid, ACT, Australia|date=21 October 1980|accessdate=9 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite AHD|13264|St Johns Schoolhouse Museum, 45 Constitution Av, Reid, ACT, Australia|date=21 October 1980|accessdate=9 December 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite AHD|13263|St Johns Church Precinct, 1 Anzac Park West, Reid, ACT, Australia|date=21 October 1980|accessdate=9 December 2019 }}</ref> The church, churchyard and Schoolhouse Mueseum are now listed by the ACT Heritage Council, which notes in particular that the East and West [[lychgate|Lychgates]] at St John's are a rare example of this type of structure in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://client14.matrix01.act.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/148470/220.pdf |title=20019. St.John the Baptist Church and Churchyard (Entry to the ACT Heritage Register) |publisher=ACT Heritage Council |accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interior==\n[[File:St Johns Church Canberra-5 (5674776239).jpg|thumb|Chancel and east window depicting scenes related to Saint John the Baptist]]\nThe church's interior is lined with memorials to parishioners, from earlier pastoral families to eminent Australians after Australia's federation. Prominent memorials include those for Sir [[Robert Garran]], Sir [[Littleton Groom]], [[H. V. Evatt]], Sir [[William McKell]], Major General Sir [[William Bridges (general)|William Bridges]] and General Sir [[Brudenell White]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref>  <ref>{{cite web |title=Take a step back in time and get in touch with Canberra's early history |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>  Extensive use of stained glass is evident in the chancel, the nave and within the tower. The chancel's east window was added between 1872 and 1874,<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a step back in time and get in touch with Canberra's early history |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>  and depicts biblical scenes related to [[Saint John the Baptist]], after whom the church is dedicated.<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Stained Glass Windows |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/st-johns-stained-glass-windows |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The east window was designed by William Macleod and made by the Sydney firm of John Falconer. It is one of the earliest Australian stained glass windows and was a prize-winning window at the Sydney Exhibition in 1973 before its installation at the church.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Randall |title=Sanctuary in the city : the Anglican Church of St John the Baptist Canberra |date=2012 |publisher=The Anglican Church of St John the Baptist, Canberra |isbn=9780646574455}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our magnificent East Window |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/photos |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSt John's has had a long association with the [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]], which is also situated on land originally held by Robert Campbell. The regimental colours of the (World War I) [[3rd_Battalion_(Australia)#Inter_war_years|Werriwa Regiment]] and the historic colours of the Royal Military College, Duntroon (given by the Duke of York while opening parliament in 1927) are [[Military colours, standards and guidons|\"laid up\"]] in the church, beneath the organ gallery.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref>  \n\nIn the side chapel on the north edge is a small bamboo cross with the words \"Reconciliation and Repentance\". The cross was presented to the church by the presiding bishop of the Anglican Church in Japan, Bishop Michael Yashiro, on 9 June 1950 in the years following the Second World War.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Randall |title=Sanctuary in the city : the Anglican Church of St John the Baptist Canberra |date=2012 |publisher=The Anglican Church of St John the Baptist, Canberra |isbn=9780646574455}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our magnificent East Window |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/photos |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> It serves as a memorial to Sister May Hayman, a staff member at the Canberra Hospital and a parishioner at St John's, who was one of ten Australian Anglican missionaries who were killed by Japanese soldiers during the war.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sister May Hayman |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/may-hayman |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=Sydney Morning Herald, cited on the St John's Church website |date=10 June 1950}}</ref> In September 2014, Bishop Andrew Yatuka Nakamura, the Bishop of Kobe, and his wife visited Canberra and attended a service at St John\u2019s to give thanks for the relationship that now exists between the people of Japan and Australia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sister May Hayman |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/may-hayman |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\nSt John's has had several organs installed throughout its history. The present pipe organ, built by [[Ronald Sharp]] and installed in 1981, is the builder's last major instrument. It is a 2-manual tracker action instrument located in the west gallery, with a case made of Western Australian [[Eucalyptus marginata|jarrah]] and tin facade pipes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hastie |first1=Kelvin |title=The Sharp Organ in the Anglican Church of St John the Baptist, Canberra |journal=Sydney Organ Journal |volume=12 |issue=6 |pages=31\u201333}}</ref> Sharp built many other significant Australian pipe organs including the [[Sydney Opera House Grand Organ|Sydney Opera House Concert Hall organ]] and organs at [[St Mary's Cathedral, Sydney]], the [[Canberra School of Music]], the [[Perth Concert Hall, Western Australia|Perth Concert Hall]] and [[Knox Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://ohta.org.au/organs/organs/CanberraSharp.html |title=St John's Anglican Church, Reid, Canberra |publisher=[[Organ Historical Trust of Australia]] |date=2006 |accessdate=9 December 2019 }}</ref> The gallery had to be extended and strengthened in the mid-1970s in anticipation of the new organ.<ref>{{cite web |title=Choir and Pipe Organ |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/choir |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe church's first organ, a single manual tracker instrument of English origin was installed circa 1862 and is now located at St Luke's Anglican Church, Deakin, several kilometres away. A second instrument, built in 1933 by Hill, Norman & Beard had five extended ranks with electro-pneumatic action. It was sold for private use in 1979.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hastie |first1=Kelvin |title=The Sharp Organ in the Anglican Church of St John the Baptist, Canberra |journal=Sydney Organ Journal |volume=12 |issue=6 |pages=31\u201333}}</ref>\n\nSt John's Choir is a [[Four-part harmony|four-part]] volunteer choir which sings at the traditional [[Book of Common Prayer]] services of [[Mattins]] and [[Evensong]].<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Choir |url=http://www.stjohnschoir.org/ |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Although usually accompanied by the organ, extra instruments such as keyboard, flute and trumpet are used on special occasions such as weddings and church festivals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Choir and Pipe Organ |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/choir |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bells==\n\nThe peal of eight church bells were donated by Governor-General [[William Sidney, 1st Viscount De L'Isle]] and mark his term of office (1961\u201365).<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bells of St John's |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/the-bells |publisher=St John's Canberra |date= |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> They were presented as a memorial to his wife Jacqueline. The bells were cast at the bell foundry of [[John Taylor & Co]] in Loughborough, United Kingdom\u2014the same foundry as the National Carillon<ref>{{cite web |title=National Carillon |url=https://www.nca.gov.au/carillon |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \u2014and were installed in 1964. They range in weight from 13 to 2 hundredweight and in diameter from 3 feet 4.5 inches to 1 foot 9 inches. The bells are rung in the English [[change ringing]] tradition, but with ropes which cause the bell clapper to strike the inside of the bell (as opposed to [[full circle ringing]]). They are rung by two people each ringing four bells. The bells are rung at selected Sunday services, for weddings and funerals, and for special occasions. When required, hymns and other melodies can also be rung.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bells of St John's |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/the-bells |publisher=St John's Canberra |date= |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Church precinct==\n[[File:St John the Baptist Church and graves in Reid, ACT.jpg|thumb|Cemetery and churchyard]]\n\n===Churchyard===\nSt John's churchyard contains Canberra's original cemetery. The first burial in the churchyard was on 3 May 1944.<ref name=\"Salisbury\">{{Cite book |last=Salisbury |first=Jean |title=St John's Churchyard Canberra |publisher=Heraldry & Genealogy Society of Canberra Inc |year=2000 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref> \n\n[[File:St John the Baptist Church April 2013.jpg|thumb|Grave (left) of the widow of Major General Sir William Bridges, the first Australian [[Chief of Army (Australia)|Chief of the General Staff]]]]\n\nThe mortal remains of many pioneers of the Canberra district are interred at St John's. They include the church's long-serving 19th-century rector, the Revd [[Pierce Galliard Smith]], and Colonel [[Colonel John George Nathaniel Gibbes (1787-1873)|John George Nathaniel Gibbes]], who occupied [[Government House, Canberra|Yarralumla]] homestead from 1859 until his death 14 years later. Gibbes was reputed to be the illegitimate son of a royal duke. Coincidentally, lying close to Gibbes' grave is the final resting place of another person with a link to the British throne, albeit one greatly separated in time and circumstance from that of the colonel. That person is [[Viscount Dunrossil]], a former [[Governor-General of Australia]], who died in office in 1961.<ref name=\"Salisbury\">{{Cite book |last=Salisbury |first=Jean |title=St John's Churchyard Canberra |publisher=Heraldry & Genealogy Society of Canberra Inc |year=2000 }}</ref>\n\nAlso interred in the churchyard are the remains of Colonel Gibbes' wife, Elizabeth, his son Augustus Gibbes (Yarralumla's proprietor from 1859 to 1881), his grandson Henry Edmund Gibbes, and his great-grandson, the Australian air ace [[Bobby Gibbes]] DSO, DFC and bar\u2014as well as St Christopher Battye and members of the pioneering McDonald, Guise, Shumack and Campbell families. The McDonalds are of Cranachan, Inverness Shire, Scotland, the same lineage as Flora Hannah McKillop (McDonald), mother of the Australian saint Mary McKillop. This information is drawn ''inter alia'' from the definitive guide to all known burials at the site, Jean Salisbury's ''St John's Churchyard Canberra''.<ref name=\"Salisbury\">{{Cite book |last=Salisbury |first=Jean |title=St John's Churchyard Canberra |publisher=Heraldry & Genealogy Society of Canberra Inc |year=2000 }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 November 1845, a local Canberran, Sarah Webb, was buried at the newly consecrated St John's church and churchyard. Her headstone reads, \"For here we have no continuing city but seek one to come\", a slightly inexact quote of Hebrews 13:14. The biblical passage refers to a heavenly city hoped for by believers. Within a few decades after Webb's death it became apparent that the area was going to be the site of the future national capital. The quote on Webb's headstone started attracting notice, with many taking the passage to be a strange and coincidental prophecy of the coming city of Canberra. The prophetic tombstone, or \"Prophet\u2019s Tombstone\" as it eventually was known, rather quickly became a local landmark with travellers  visiting it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a step back in time and get in touch with Canberra's early history |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe churchyard was closed to new burials in 1937 unless exclusive rights to a plot were held.<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Churchyard |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/st-johns-churchyard |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Schoolhouse museum===\n[[File:St John's Schoolhouse Museum.jpg|thumb|St John's Schoolhouse Museum]]\nCanberra\u2019s first schoolhouse was built in the first half of the 19th century by [[Robert Campbell (Australian landowner)|Robert Campbell]] of Duntroon for the education of workers\u2019 children. Consisting of a schoolroom with five attached rooms it served as the residence for the schoolmaster and his family. The building was constructed from rubble and bluestone quarried locally, with shingle roof and the walls two feet thick to afford protection from Canberra\u2019s harsh climate. The first students arrived in 1845 and it was the only school on the Limestone Plains until 1880 when the first public school was opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Church |url=https://www.canberratracks.act.gov.au/heritage-trails/track-2-the-limestone-plains/st-johns-church |publisher=Canberra Tracks |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Children walked across the fields to attend school and pioneering families on the school roll include the Blundell children who lived in nearby [[Blundell's Cottage]], one of the few stone buildings of its type to have survived intact in the [[Australian Capital Territory]].<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Schoolhouse Museum |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/st-johns-schoolhouse |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe schoolhouse closed in 1907 and reopened in 1969 as a museum containing records and artifacts from Canberra's rural and recent past. Scrapbooks dating from 1954 to the present are held at the museum. They consist of newspaper cuttings, brochures, photos, letters and journal articles relating to the schoolhouse, the church, other Canberra churches, the Campbell family and the history of Canberra. Royal visits, heritage issues and other local interest stories are also held on site.<ref>{{cite web |title=St John's Schoolhouse Museum | url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/st-johns-schoolhouse |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Rectory===\nThe rectory, the residence of the rector of Canberra, lies in the southeastern corner of the church precinct, opening onto Anzac Parade. It was completed in 1923.<ref name=\"Body\">{{Cite book |last=Body |first=A. H. |title=Firm Still You Stand |publisher=St John's Parish Council |year=1986 }}</ref> The original rectory of St John's was built in 1873 in what is now [[Glebe Park, Canberra|Glebe Park]] in inner Canberra. The first occupant was the Revd Pierre Galliard Smith, who surrounded the rectory with poplars, elms, willows and hawthorns.<ref>{{cite web |title=Plaque commemorating opening of Glebe Park, photograph of the plaque available at the URL |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/photos?lightbox=dataItem-j4kx928w |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The survivors and descendants of those trees remain in today's Glebe Park. From 1926 to early 1928 the old rectory was leased from the government by an Anglican religious order, the Community of the Sisters of the Church, or the Kilburn Sisters, to found St Gabriel's school which later became the [[Canberra Girls' Grammar School]].<ref name=\"Body\">{{Cite book |last=Body |first=A. H. |title=Firm Still You Stand |publisher=St John's Parish Council |year=1986 }}</ref>\n\n===Church hall===\n[[File:St John mural in the hall of the St John the Baptist Church, Reid, Canberra.jpg|thumb|Mural painting in church hall]]\nAdjacent to St John's is the church hall. The hall has a [[mural]] [[painting]] at its southern end which depicts people and events from the life of the church and the region. Rendered in a simplistic style, the mural depicts subjects as diverse as a [[theodolite]], a [[microscope]], an [[Australian aborigine]] man, [[Bogong moth]]s, [[Merino sheep]], [[liturgy|liturgical]] symbols, the [[Guides Australia]] logo and a girl in the uniform, a [[Scouts Australia|Boy Scout]], [[Old Parliament House, Canberra]], early ministers of the church and settlers including Robert Campbell and his nearby house, \"Duntroon\" (also shown), which is now part of the Royal Military College, Duntroon. The church hall provides a facility for events and meetings and also houses the office of the parish of Canberra.<ref>{{cite web |title=Venue Use and Hire |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/venue-use-and-hire |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Contemporary references==\n[[File:St John the Baptist Church, Reid ACT - HRH Queen Elizabeth II - 23Oct11.jpg|thumb|Queen Elizabeth II emerges from St John's after a service on 23 October 2011]]\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth and Prince Phillip with Canberra Anglicans 23Oct11.jpg|thumb|left|[[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] talking with the rector, the Revd Paul Black, and Prince Philip with the [[Anglican Diocese of Canberra and Goulburn|Bishop of Canberra and Goulburn]] the Rt Revd [[Stuart Robinson (bishop)|Stuart Robinson]]]]\n\nToday, St John's holds both traditional and contemporary worship services. Traditional Book of Common Prayer (17th century language) services are held  at 7:00 am, 8:00 am and 11:15 am on Sundays. Contemporary services are held at 9:30 am and 6:00 pm. Once a month, a choral evensong service is held at 5:00 pm. There are also weekday services held from Tuesday to Friday at 8:30 am, along with a meditation service on Wednesdays at 5:00 pm.<ref>{{cite web |title=Christian meditation |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/christian-meditation |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The building is open every day for private prayer, visitors and tourists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sunday and weekday service times |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/sunday-and-weekday-worship-times |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nFormer [[Prime Minister of Australia]], [[Kevin Rudd]], and his wife, [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Rein]], regularly attended the church during 2009\u20132010. Rudd and Rein had been married in St John's, and their eldest son had been baptised there. Rudd took the opportunity to address the assembled media and television cameras after Sunday services and field and answer questions on topics of the day.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.abc.net.au/offair/2009/10/rudd-squanders-chance-to-practise-what-he-preaches.html |title=Rudd squanders chance to practise what he preaches |author=Uhlmann, Chris |author-link=Chris Uhlmann |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |access-date=22 October 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rudd |first1=Kevin |title=Church-going folk aren't political property of the Tories |url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/church-going-folk-aren-t-political-property-of-the-tories-20190604-p51uaa |publisher=Australian Financial Review |date=4 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=More than just a light on the hill |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/more-than-just-a-light-on-the-hill-20071222-gdru68.html |publisher=Sydney Morning Herald |date=22 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the visit of the [[Queen of Australia]] in October 2011, [[Queen regent|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip]] attended St John's for the 11:15 am service on 23 October 2011. She was welcomed by the rector, the Revd Canon Paul Black, and the [[Anglican Diocese of Canberra and Goulburn|Bishop of Canberra and Goulburn]], the Rt Revd [[Stuart Robinson (bishop)|Stuart Robinson]]. Kevin Rudd and Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Rein were among the 120 guests at the service. The visit was Queen Elizabeth II's sixth to St John's.<ref>{{cite web |title=Queen meets Rush, attends church service |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-10-23/queen-to-host-luncheon-at-government-house/3595662 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Queen cheered at church |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6172622/queen-cheered-at-church/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=The Canberra Times |date=23 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 September 2018, members of the Orthodox community gathered to celebrate the 70th anniversary of the first Ukrainian Orthodox service in Australia, which was held at St John's on 26 September 1948. The church had been the home for Australian Ukrainian Orthodox faithful in Canberra until they built their own church in 1959. Bishop Daniel Zelinsky of South Bound Brook, New Jersey, celebrated the Divine Liturgy and preached in Ukrainian and English.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ukrainian Orthodox Celebrate 70 Years |url=https://catholicukes.org.au/ukrainian-orthodox-celebrate-70-years/ |publisher=Ukrainian Catholic Church, Australia, New Zealand and Oceania |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ukrainian Orthodox Liturgy |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/photos?lightbox=dataItem-jmoj79x7 |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, St John's celebrated its 175th anniversary since its 1845 consecration. A special 10:00 am choral service was held, attended by the Governor General, [[David Hurley]], and the [[List of ambassadors of the United States to Australia|Ambassador of the United States]], [[Arthur B. Culvahouse Jr.|Arthur Culvahouse]]. The sermon was delivered by the [[Anglican Diocese of Canberra and Goulburn|Bishop of Canberra and Goulburn]], the Rt Revd [[Mark Short]]. St John's was described as \"an English village church and through a quirk of history they literally put the national capital around us\".<ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref> The service was the last to be held before the church closed temporarily as a result of the 2020 [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide coronavirus pandemic]], with services being recorded and distributed online.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Steve |title=Isolation diary: Free at last ... to do what? |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6701785/free-at-last-to-do-what/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=The Canberra Times |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Steve |title=Coronavirus: churches move to online innovations ahead of Easter |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6713285/churches-embrace-online-intervention-ahead-of-easter-celebration/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |publisher=The Canberra Times |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Incumbents==\nThe Revd Canon Paul Black is the current incumbent of St John's and rector of Canberra.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ministry Team |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/ministry-team-1 |publisher=St John's Church |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> The first incumbent, the Revd Edward Smith, was rector of the Queanbeayan parish, of which St John's was then part. The longest serving incumbent was Pierce Galliard Smith, who served as rector for 51 years from 1855 to 1905.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref>  \n\nThe following have served as rector of St John's:<ref>{{cite web |title=Take a step back in time and get in touch with Canberra's early history |url=https://www.stjohnscanberra.org/history |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A Service to Celebrate 175 Years of Christian Worship on the Limestone Plains |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=St John's Anglican Church Canberra}}</ref>  \n\n* Edward Smith (Rector of Queanbeyan) (1845\u20131850)\n* George Gregory (1850\u20131851)\n* Thomas Wilkinson (1851\u20131854)\n* [[Pierce Galliard Smith]] (1855\u20131905)\n* Arthur Hopcraft (1905\u20131909)\n* Arthur Champion (1909\u20131913)\n* Frederick Ward (1913\u20131929)\n* Charles Robertson (1930\u20131949)\n* Robert Davies (1949\u20131953)\n* Robert Gordon Arthur (1953\u20131960)\n* Frederick Hill (1960\u20131972)\n* [[Owen Dowling]] (1972\u20131981)\n* Ian George (1981\u20131989)\n* David Oliphant (1989\u20131995)\n* Allan Ewing (1996\u20132003)\n* Gregory Thompson (2004\u20132007)\n* Paul Black (2008\u2013present)\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|Australian Capital Territory|Christianity}}}}\n* [[St Paul's Church, Manuka]]\n* [[:Category:Churches in Canberra|List of churches in Canberra]]\n* [[:Category:Landmarks in Canberra|List of Canberra landmarks]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.stjohnscanberra.org/ Official website]\n\n\n{{-}}\n{{Anglican Church of Australia}}\n{{Canberra landmarks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint John the Baptist Church Reid}}\n[[Category:Cemeteries in the Australian Capital Territory]]\n[[Category:Churches in Canberra]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1845]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican church buildings]]\n[[Category:1845 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Sandstone churches in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Capital Territory Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Anglican Diocese of Canberra and Goulburn]]\n[[Category:Australian Capital Territory places listed on the defunct Register of the National Estate]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Canberra]]\n[[Category:Bluestone churches in Australia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Canberra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox church\n| icon                   =\n| icon_width             =\n| icon_alt               =\n| name                   = St John's Anglican Church\n| fullname               = \n| other name             = \n| native_name            = \n| native_name_lang       = \n| image                  = Church of St John Canberra-1 (39648211152).jpg\n| image_size             = 270\n| alt                    = \n| caption                = Exterior in 2017\n\n| pushpin